{"title_page": "Umar ibn al-Walid", "text_new": "'''Umar ibn al-Walid ibn Abd al-Malik''' ({{floruit|705|744}}) was an [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad]] prince, commander in the [[Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]] and the governor of [[Jund al-Urdunn]] (district of Jordan) during the reign of his father [[al-Walid I]] ({{reign|705|715}}). He may have patronized the [[Desert castles|Umayyad desert palaces]] of [[Khirbat al-Minya]] in modern Israel and [[Qasr Kharana]] in modern Jordan.\n\n==Life==\nUmar was a son of the [[Umayyad]] caliph [[al-Walid I]], who appointed him governor of [[Jund al-Urdunn]] (the military district of Jordan; e.g. modern southern Lebanon, northern Israel and northern Jordan).{{sfn|Crone|1980|p=126}} He was the commander of the Hajj pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] in November 707.{{sfn|Hinds|1990|p=145}} In 710/11, Umar led an expedition against [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] territory alongside his uncle [[Maslama ibn Abd al-Malik]].{{sfn|Hinds|1990|p=182}} As governor of Jund al-Urdunn, Umar apparently questioned [[Peter of Capitolias]], who was made a Christian saint, at some point before his adjudication and execution by al-Walid I.{{sfn|Sahner|2020|p=167}}\n\nRepresenting the interests of Marwanid (Umayyad ruling house) princes negatively affected by Caliph [[Umar II]]'s ({{reign|717|720}}) economic policies, which reversed al-Walid I's liberal distribution of war spoils among members of the ruling family, Umar wrote a letter to the caliph; in it he accuses the caliph of abandoning his predecessor's policies, accusing them of oppression and detesting their descendants, to which the caliph responded by alleging the Umayyads abandoned the correct path by misusing public funds, illicitly shedding blood and ruling tyrannically.{{sfn|Murad|1985|p=328}} He is recorded by the sources being in a lawsuit in 738/39 with the [[Alid]] rebel leader [[Zayd ibn Ali]], which was settled by Caliph [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]].{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1989|p=18}} He is recorded again having a dispute with his cousin, Caliph [[al-Walid II]] ({{reign|743|744}}) over a slave girl seized by the caliph.{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1989|p=18}} According to the historian [[al-Ya'qubi]] (d. 897), Umar led the tribes of Jund al-Urdunn against his half-brother Caliph [[Yazid III]] ({{reign|744|744}}) during the [[Third Fitna|Third Muslim civil war]].{{sfn|Biesterfeldt|G\u00fcnther|2018|p=1057}}\n\nUmar may have patronized the construction of the [[Khirbat al-Minya]] palace near the [[Sea of Galilee]], according to [[Jere Bacharach]].{{sfn|Bacharach|1996|p=35}} Umar is mentioned in numerous Arabic inscriptions found in the [[Syrian Desert]] palace of [[Qasr Kharana]] in modern Jordan, about 60 kilometers east of Amman.{{sfn|Bisheh|1992|pp=38\u201341}} The inscriptions attest to visits by the prince at the beginning of the 8th century.{{sfn|Imbert|1998|p=49, note 9}} The names of his sons Abd al-Malik and Abd Allah are each mentioned at least once in the inscriptions as well. The palace likely served as a resting place between Syria and Mecca.{{sfn|Bisheh|1992|pp=38\u201341}}\n\n==Descendants==\nUmar was dubbed the \"the stallion of the Banu Marwan (the Marwanids)\" or \"the stud of the Banu Umayya (the Umayyads)\" for his numerous marriages and his fathering of some sixty sons.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=304, note 57}}{{sfn|Bisheh|1992|p=39}} Among his wives was Umm Abd Allah bint Habib, a granddaughter of [[al-Hakam ibn Abi al-As]] (Umar's paternal great-great-grandfather) with whom he had his son Abd al-Malik.{{sfn|Robinson|2020|p=148}}{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=114, note 9}} Abd al-Malik's son Habib escaped the massacre of the Umayyad family at Nahr Abi Futrus in the aftermath of the [[Abbasid Revolution]] of 750 and established himself in the [[Umayyad emirate]] in [[al-Andalus]] (the [[Iberian Peninsula]]).{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=115}} There, the founder of the emirate, Habib's distant cousin [[Abd al-Rahman I]], appointed him governor of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] and granted him properties around [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Cordoba]], [[Cabra, Spain|Cabra]], [[Rayyu]] ([[M\u00e1laga]] and [[Archidona]]) and [[Porcuna]].{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=115}} His descendants were an influential family known as the Habibi clan.{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=115}} Umar's sons Isa and Hafs also relocated to al-Andalus. Descendants of Abd al-Malik and Isa are named by the sources as members of the Umayyad elite in al-Andalus up to the late 10th century.{{sfn|Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9|1992|pp=418\u2013423}}{{sfn|Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9|1994|p=458}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Bacharach |first1=Jere L. |authorlink=Jere L. Bacharach |editor1-last=Necpo\u011flu |editor1-first=G\u00fclru |title=Muqarnas: An Annual on the Visual Culture of the Islamic World, Volume 13 |date=1996 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=90-04-10633-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NdCTI5FqayAC |chapter=Marwanid Umayyad Building Activities: Speculations on Patronage|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Biesterfeldt |first1=Hinrich |last2=G\u00fcnther |first2=Sebastian |title=The Works of Ibn W\u0101\u1e0di\u1e25 al-Ya\u02bfq\u016bb\u012b (Volume 3): An English Translation |date=2018 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-35621-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHxTDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bisheh |first1=Ghazi |editor1-last=Kerner |editor1-first=Susanne |title=The Near East in Antiquity: German Contributions to the Archaeology of Jordan, Palestine, Syria, Lebanon, and Egypt, Volume 3 |date=1992 |publisher=Al-Kutba |location=Amman |pages=35-41 |url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=kK1tAAAAMAAJ |ref=harv |chapter=The Umayyad Monuments Between Muwaqqar and Azraq: Palatial Residences or Caravanserais?}}\n*{{The End of the Jihad State}}\n*{{Slaves on Horses}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=26 |url={{Google Books||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=23 |url={{Google Books|XEsflZBlADwC|plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Imbert |first1=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |title=Inscriptions et graffiti arabes de jordanie: quelques r\u00e9flexiones sur l'\u00e9tablissement d'un r\u00e9cent corpus |journal=Quaderni di Studi Arabi |date=1998 |volume=16 |pages=45\u201358 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/25802846 |language=French |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Murad |first1=Hasan Qasim |title=Was 'Umar II \"a True Umayyad\"? |journal=Islamic Studies |date=Autumn 1985 |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=325\u2013348 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/20839728 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Robinson |first1=Majied |title=Marriage in the Tribe of Muhammad: A Statistical Study of Early Arabic Genealogical Literature |date=2020 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |location=Berlin |isbn=9783110624168 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TiXGDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sahner |first1=Christian C. |title=Christian Martyrs Under Islam: Religious Violence and the Making of the Muslim World |date=2020 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton and Oxford |isbn=978-0-691-17910-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TZqzDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Scales |first1=Peter C. |title=The Fall of the Caliphate of Cordoba: Berbers and Arabs in Conflict |date=1994 |publisher=E. J. Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=90-04-09868-2 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9 |first1=Ar\u00e1nzazu |editor1-last=Mar\u00edn |editor1-first=Manuela |editor2-last=Jes\u00fas |editor2-first=Zan\u00f3n |title=Estudios onom\u00e1stico-biogr\u00e1ficos de Al-Andalus: V |date=1992 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-07265-0 |pages=373\u2013432 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vXBiWrMmcG0C |ref=harv |chapter=La Familia Omeya en al-Andalus |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9 |first1=Ar\u00e1nzazu |editor1-last=Mar\u00edn |editor1-first=Manuela |title=Estudios onom\u00e1stico-biogr\u00e1ficos de Al-Andalus: V |date=1994 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-07415-7 |pages=445\u2013462 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sTvD7V9qbUIC&pg=PA446 |ref=harv |chapter=Otros Linajes Omeyas en al-Andalus |language=Spanish}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:Third Fitna]]\n[[Category:Umayyad dynasty]]\n[[Category:Umayyad people of the Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Jordan]]\n", "text_old": "'''Umar ibn al-Walid ibn Abd al-Malik''' ({{floruit|705|744}}) was an [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad]] prince, commander in the [[Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]] and the governor of [[Jund al-Urdunn]] (district of Jordan) during the reign of his father [[al-Walid I]] ({{reign|705|715}}). He may have patronized the [[Desert castles|Umayyad desert palaces]] of [[Khirbat al-Minya]] in modern Israel and [[Qasr Kharana]] in modern Jordan.\n\n==Life==\nUmar was a son of the [[Umayyad]] caliph [[al-Walid I]], who appointed him governor of [[Jund al-Urdunn]] (the military district of Jordan; e.g. modern southern Lebanon, northern Israel and northern Jordan).{{sfn|Crone|1980|p=126}} He was the commander of the Hajj pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] in November 707.{{sfn|Hinds|1990|p=145}} In 710/11, Umar led an expedition against [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] territory alongside his uncle [[Maslama ibn Abd al-Malik]].{{sfn|Hinds|1990|p=182}} As governor of Jund al-Urdunn, Umar apparently questioned [[Peter of Capitolias]], who was made a Christian saint, at some point before his adjudication and execution by al-Walid I.{{sfn|Sahner|2020|p=167}}\n\nRepresenting the interests of Marwanid (Umayyad ruling house) princes negatively affected by Caliph [[Umar II]]'s ({{reign|717|720}}) economic policies, which reversed al-Walid I's liberal distribution of war spoils among members of the ruling family, Umar wrote a letter to the caliph; in it he accuses the caliph of abandoning his predecessor's policies, accusing them of oppression and detesting their descendants, to which the caliph responded by alleging the Umayyads abandoned the correct path by misusing public funds, illicitly shedding blood and ruling tyrannically.{{sfn|Murad|1985|p=328}} He is recorded by the sources being in a lawsuit in 738/39 with the [[Alid]] rebel leader [[Zayd ibn Ali]], which was settled by Caliph [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]].{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1989|p=18}} He is recorded again having a dispute with his cousin, Caliph [[al-Walid II]] ({{reign|743|744}}) over a slave girl seized by the caliph.{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1989|p=18}} According to the historian [[al-Ya'qubi]] (d. 897), Umar led the tribes of Jund al-Urdunn against his half-brother Caliph [[Yazid III]] ({{reign|744|744}}) during the [[Third Fitna|Third Muslim civil war]].{{sfn|Biesterfeldt|G\u00fcnther|2018|p=1057}}\n\nUmar may have patronized the construction of the [[Khirbat al-Minya]] palace near the [[Sea of Galilee]], according to [[Jere Bacharach]].{{sfn|Bacharach|1996|p=35}} Umar is mentioned in numerous Arabic inscriptions found in the [[Syrian Desert]] palace of [[Qasr Kharana]] in modern Jordan, about 60 kilometers east of Amman.{{sfn|Bisheh|1992|pp=38\u201341}} The inscriptions attest to visits by the prince at the beginning of the 8th century.{{sfn|Imbert|1998|p=49, note 9}} The names of his sons Abd al-Malik and Abd Allah are each mentioned at least once in the inscriptions as well. The palace likely served as a resting place between Syria and Mecca.{{sfn|Bisheh|1992|pp=38\u201341}}\n\n==Descendants==\nUmar was dubbed the \"the stallion of the Banu Marwan (the Marwanids)\" or \"the stud of the Banu Umayya (the Umayyads)\" for his numerous marriages and his fathering of some sixty sons.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=304, note 57}}{{sfn|Bisheh|1992|p=39}} Among his wives was Umm Abd Allah bint Habib, a granddaughter of [[al-Hakam ibn Abi al-As]] (Umar's paternal great-great-grandfather) with whom he had his son Abd al-Malik.{{sfn|Robinson|2020|p=148}}{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=114, note 9}} Abd al-Malik's son Habib escaped the massacre of the Umayyad family at Nahr Abi Futrus in the aftermath of the [[Abbasid Revolution]] of 750 and established himself in the [[Umayyad emirate]] in [[al-Andalus]] (the [[Iberian Peninsula]]).{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=115}} There, the founder of the emirate, Habib's distant cousin [[Abd al-Rahman I]], appointed him governor of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] and granted him properties around [[Cordoba]], [[Cabra, Spain|Cabra]], [[Rayyu]] ([[M\u00e1laga]] and [[Archidona]]) and [[Porcuna]].{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=115}} His descendants were an influential family known as the Habibi clan.{{sfn|Scales|1994|p=115}} Umar's sons Isa and Hafs also relocated to al-Andalus. Descendants of Abd al-Malik and Isa are named by the sources as members of the Umayyad elite in al-Andalus up to the late 10th century.{{sfn|Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9|1992|pp=418\u2013423}}{{sfn|Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9|1994|p=458}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Bacharach |first1=Jere L. |authorlink=Jere L. Bacharach |editor1-last=Necpo\u011flu |editor1-first=G\u00fclru |title=Muqarnas: An Annual on the Visual Culture of the Islamic World, Volume 13 |date=1996 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=90-04-10633-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NdCTI5FqayAC |chapter=Marwanid Umayyad Building Activities: Speculations on Patronage|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Biesterfeldt |first1=Hinrich |last2=G\u00fcnther |first2=Sebastian |title=The Works of Ibn W\u0101\u1e0di\u1e25 al-Ya\u02bfq\u016bb\u012b (Volume 3): An English Translation |date=2018 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-35621-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHxTDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bisheh |first1=Ghazi |editor1-last=Kerner |editor1-first=Susanne |title=The Near East in Antiquity: German Contributions to the Archaeology of Jordan, Palestine, Syria, Lebanon, and Egypt, Volume 3 |date=1992 |publisher=Al-Kutba |location=Amman |pages=35-41 |url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=kK1tAAAAMAAJ |ref=harv |chapter=The Umayyad Monuments Between Muwaqqar and Azraq: Palatial Residences or Caravanserais?}}\n*{{The End of the Jihad State}}\n*{{Slaves on Horses}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=26 |url={{Google Books||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=23 |url={{Google Books|XEsflZBlADwC|plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Imbert |first1=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |title=Inscriptions et graffiti arabes de jordanie: quelques r\u00e9flexiones sur l'\u00e9tablissement d'un r\u00e9cent corpus |journal=Quaderni di Studi Arabi |date=1998 |volume=16 |pages=45\u201358 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/25802846 |language=French |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Murad |first1=Hasan Qasim |title=Was 'Umar II \"a True Umayyad\"? |journal=Islamic Studies |date=Autumn 1985 |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=325\u2013348 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/20839728 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Robinson |first1=Majied |title=Marriage in the Tribe of Muhammad: A Statistical Study of Early Arabic Genealogical Literature |date=2020 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |location=Berlin |isbn=9783110624168 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TiXGDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sahner |first1=Christian C. |title=Christian Martyrs Under Islam: Religious Violence and the Making of the Muslim World |date=2020 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton and Oxford |isbn=978-0-691-17910-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TZqzDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Scales |first1=Peter C. |title=The Fall of the Caliphate of Cordoba: Berbers and Arabs in Conflict |date=1994 |publisher=E. J. Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=90-04-09868-2 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9 |first1=Ar\u00e1nzazu |editor1-last=Mar\u00edn |editor1-first=Manuela |editor2-last=Jes\u00fas |editor2-first=Zan\u00f3n |title=Estudios onom\u00e1stico-biogr\u00e1ficos de Al-Andalus: V |date=1992 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-07265-0 |pages=373\u2013432 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vXBiWrMmcG0C |ref=harv |chapter=La Familia Omeya en al-Andalus |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9 |first1=Ar\u00e1nzazu |editor1-last=Mar\u00edn |editor1-first=Manuela |title=Estudios onom\u00e1stico-biogr\u00e1ficos de Al-Andalus: V |date=1994 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-07415-7 |pages=445\u2013462 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sTvD7V9qbUIC&pg=PA446 |ref=harv |chapter=Otros Linajes Omeyas en al-Andalus |language=Spanish}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:Third Fitna]]\n[[Category:Umayyad dynasty]]\n[[Category:Umayyad people of the Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Jordan]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toC\u00f3rdoba(link changed toC\u00f3rdoba, Spain) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umar_ibn_al-Walid"}
{"title_page": "Gurdwara Gobind Ghat", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurdwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 = \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in India\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = India\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = Guru\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = \n}}\n'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Kangan Ghat,  is situated on the bank of river Ganges, about 200 yards from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]. While [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold bangle there, it is also the place where he blessed mental peace to Pandit Shiv Dutt, by giving him the knowledge of Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji. Guru Sahib Ji taught him what 9 gurus had preached.\n\nThe [[ghat]]is associated whith Guru Gobind Singh's childhood, as he was often found playing with his playmates on the banks of the [[Ganges]].  This [[ghat]] about one furlong from [[Takht Shri Harmandir Saheb]] and is marked by a gateway over which this [[Gurdwara]] is situated in a single room. The river has since receded away to the north.\nhttps://www.allaboutsikhs.com/gurudwaras-in-india/gurdwara-gobind-ghat-patna-bihar\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurdwara Gobind Ghat is also known as [[Gurdwara Kangan Ghat]]\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110808112424/http://www.sridasamgranth.com/ Sri Dasam Granth]'',The Sri Dasam Granth Sahib website\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Gurdwaras in Bihar]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurdwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 = \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in India\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = India\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = Guru\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = \n}}\n'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat'''  situated on the bank of river Ganges is hardly 200 yards from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]. It is also popular as Kangan Ghat where young [[Guru Gobind Singh]] had thrown his gold bangle. On the other hand young Guru Gobind Singh had blessed mental peace to Pandit Shiv Dutt, by giving him the knowledge of Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji. Guru Sahib Ji taught him what 9 gurus had preached.\n\nHere the child Guru Gobind Singh used to play with his playmates on the bank of the [[Ganges]].  This [[ghat]] about one furlong from [[Takht Shri Harmandir Saheb]] is marked by a gateway over which this [[Gurdwara]] is situated in a single room. The river has, however, receded since away to the north.\nhttps://www.allaboutsikhs.com/gurudwaras-in-india/gurdwara-gobind-ghat-patna-bihar\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurdwara Gobind Ghat is also known as [[Gurdwara Kangan Ghat]]\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110808112424/http://www.sridasamgranth.com/ Sri Dasam Granth]'',The Sri Dasam Granth Sahib website\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Gurdwaras in Bihar]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "name_user": "LKametVentures", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling and grammar errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurdwara_Gobind_Ghat"}
{"title_page": "Robert Poole (historian)", "text_new": "[[File:RP 2010.jpg|thumb|Robert Poole]]  \n\n'''Robert Poole''' (born 1957) is a UK-based historian, currently Professor of History at the University of Central Lancashire, Preston.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uclan.ac.uk/staff_profiles/dr_robert_poole.php|title=Staff Profiles {{!}} About us {{!}}|website=Uclan website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827162137/http://www.uclan.ac.uk/staff_profiles/dr_robert_poole.php|archive-date=2014-08-27|url-status=dead|accessdate=2017-02-18}}</ref> He gained his PhD from the University of Lancaster in 1986, where he was associated with Prof [[Harold Perkin]]'s Centre for Social History, organising the 1996 conference of the Social History Society on 'Time and the Construction of the Past'. He has also held positions at the universities of Keele, Edge Hill and Cumbria. He has also been Leverhulme Senior Visiting Research Fellow at the University of Manchester (2000-1), an Associate of the Centre for the History of Science, Technology and Medicine, University of Manchester (2010-17), an associate of 'The Future in the Stars' research programme, Friedrich-Meinecke Institut, Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin (2012-16),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geschkult.fu-berlin.de/en/e/fmi/astrofuturismus/projekt/index.html|title=The Future in the Stars: European Astroculture and Extraterrestrial Life in the Twentieth Century. Emmy Noether research group|last=|first=|date=2012|website=The Future in the Stars: European Astroculture and Extraterrestrial Life in the Twentieth Century|publisher=Friedrich-Meinecke Institut, Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin|accessdate=}}</ref> and visiting Senior Research Fellow to the History Group, University of Hertfordshire (2013-15).\n\n== Earthrise and the space age ==\nPoole's  book \"Earthrise: How Man First Saw the Earth\" (Yale University Press, 2008),<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://yalepress.yale.edu/yupbooks/book.asp?isbn=9780300164039|title = Earthrise (paperback edition)|date = |accessdate = |website = Yale University Press|last = |first = }}</ref> a study of the first views of Earth from space and their impact, has been identified as one of the key works of the 'new aerospace history'.<ref>{{Cite book|title = To Touch the Face of God: the Sacred, the Profane and the American Space Program, 1957-1975|last = Oliver|first = Kendrick|publisher = Johns Hopkins UP|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1-4214-0788-3|location = Baltimore, Maryland|pages = 4\u20135}}</ref> He has lectured on 'Earthrise' and the cultural history of the space age in [[London, England|London]], [[Washington, D.C.]], [[Lucerne]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jesslaccetti.blogspot.co.uk/2009/07/swiss-biennial-on-science-technics.html?view=flipcard|title=[Swiss Biennial on Science, Technics + Aesthetics]|website=jesslaccetti.blogspot.co.uk|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> [[Paris, France|Paris]], [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]], and [[Copenhagen]], broadcast on American public radio networks,<ref name=\"test\">[http://www.loe.org/shows/segments.htm?programID=08-P13-00050&segmentID=6 'Living on Earth']</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://backstoryradio.org/shows/starry-eyed-heavens/|title = Starry-Eyed: a History of the Heavens|date = August 2013|website = Backstory.org|publisher = Virginia Foundation for the Humanities|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141016200652/http://backstoryradio.org/shows/starry-eyed-heavens/|archivedate = 16 October 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.npr.org/2010/02/12/123614938/an-alien-view-of-earth?ps=rs|title = Pale Blue Dot|date = Feb 2012|accessdate = |website = [[National Public Radio]] (U.S.A.)|last = |first = }}</ref> and in July 2009 wrote the op ed piece for the '[[Los Angeles Times]]' on the fortieth anniversary of the Lunar landing in July 1969 by [[Apollo 11]].<ref name=\"test4\">[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1793992381.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+19%2C+2009&author=Robert+Poole&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&edition=&startpage=A.31&desc=For+the+Apollo+crews%2C+a+small+world%3B+Traveling+to+the+moon+changed+how+they+saw+the+Earth LA Times Archive 19 July 2009]</ref> Subsequent articles have explored the science fiction writer and techno-prophet [[Arthur C. Clarke]],<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.tandfonline.com/eprint/vsU4pIysUwcTmD3Stxff/full|title = The Challenge of the Spaceship: Arthur C. Clarke and the History of the Future|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = Sep 2012|journal = History and Technology|accessdate = |doi = 10.1080/07341512.2012.722793|pmid =|volume = 28|pages = 255\u2013280 }}</ref> '2001: a Space Odyssey and the Dawn of Man' in the 2015 collection ''Stanley Kubrick: New Perspectives,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackdogonline.com/imported-products-2/stanley-kubrick|title=Stanley Kubrick: New Perspectives|website=Black Dog Press|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> and the myth of progress in '2001: a Space Odyssey'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9781137369154|title=Limiting Outer Space - Astroculture After Apollo {{!}} Alexander C.T. Geppert {{!}} Palgrave Macmillan|language=en}}</ref> Another recent article, 'What was Whole about the Whole Earth?', provides a missing chapter to 'Earthrise'.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Surveillance Imperative|last = Turchetti|first = Simone|publisher = Palgrave Macmillan|year = 2014|isbn = 9781137438720|location = |pages = |url = http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/the-surveillance-imperative-simone-turchetti/?k=9781137438720|last2 = Roberts|first2 = Peder}}</ref> In early 2016 he enjoyed a Short-Term Visitor Award at the [[Smithsonian Institution]], [[National Air and Space Museum]], to look at the recently-acquired papers of Arthur C. Clarke.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Arthur C. Clarke's Personal Papers Arrive at the Museum {{!}} AirSpace|url = http://blog.nasm.si.edu/highlights-from-the-collection/clarkes-personal-papers/|website = blog.nasm.si.edu|accessdate = 2015-06-21|date = 2015-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Peterloo and popular protest ==\nPoole's forthcoming book ''Peterloo: the English Uprising,'' (OUP, 2019) is an account of the 1819 [[Peterloo massacre]] in Manchester, on which he has written articles in ''Past and Present'',<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = The March to Peterloo: Politics and Festivity in Late Georgian England|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = August 2006|journal = Past and Present |volume = 192|accessdate = |doi = 10.1093/pastj/gtl006|pmid = |issue = 1|pages = 109\u2013153}}</ref> ''History'',<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = By the law or the sword: Peterloo revisited|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = April 2006|journal = History|volume = 91|accessdate = |doi = 10.1111/j.1468-229X.2006.00366.x|pmid = |issue = 302|pages = 254\u2013276}}</ref> ''Labour History Review,''<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://clok.uclan.ac.uk/6682/1/Poole%202009%20LHR.pdf|title = French revolution or peasants' revolt? Petitioners and rebels from the Blanketeers to the Chartists|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = April 2009|journal = Labour History Review|accessdate = |doi = 10.1179/174581809X408375|pmid = |issue = 74, 1|volume = 74|pages = 6\u201326}}</ref> and edited collections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchesteruniversitypress.co.uk/9780719091698/|title=Manchester University Press - Politics, performance and popular culture|work=Manchester University Press|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref> He is  historical adviser to the Peterloo 2019 commemoration programme, run jointly by Manchester Histories and the People's History Museum,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://manchesterhistories.co.uk/projects/peterloo2019|title=Peterloo 2019 - Manchester Histories|work=Manchester Histories|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> and to the  2017-18 community project by ReelMcr, 'Our Sam, Middleton man'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themeteor.org/2017/08/19/sam-middleton-man-community-needed-help-bring-middletons-famous-son-back-life/|title='Our Sam - The Middleton Man': Community needed to help bring Middleton's most famous son back to life - The Meteor|date=2017-08-19|work=The Meteor|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>He was instrumental in bringing to the John Rylands Library a full set of the radical newspaper the ''Manchester Observer'' (1818-22),  now freely available online as part of the library's Peterloo collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://luna.manchester.ac.uk/luna/servlet/Manchester~24~24|title=Peterloo Collection|website=luna.manchester.ac.uk|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> He has given numerous public lectures and workshops, including the Manchester Histories Festivals and the 2018 BBC ''Civilisations'' festival,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PeterlooMemoria|title=Peterloo Memorial (@PeterlooMemoria) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> and is an active member of the Peterloo Memorial Campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peterloomassacre.org|title=Peterloo Massacre Memorial Campaign|website=www.peterloomassacre.org|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> His broadcast appearances include ''The Matter of the North'' episode 7 'The Radical North' (BBC R4 2016),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07syyrh|title=The Radical North, The Matter of the North - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> ''Elegance and Decadence: the Age of the Regency'' episode 3 (BBC Four, 2011), ''How the North was Built'' Part 1 (ITV, 2013), ''The Real Mill'' (Channel 4, 2014),<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Real Mill with Tony Robinson|url = http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-real-mill-with-tony-robinson|website = Channel 4|accessdate = 2015-06-21}}</ref> and the BBC Schools Programme ''Exploring the Past'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Peterloo Massacre, Exploring the Past: Protest - BBC Two|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02jg2hp|website = BBC|accessdate = 2015-06-21}}</ref> He edited a volume of the Manchester Region History Review,  ''Return to Peterloo,'' contributing essays including 'What Don't We Know About Peterloo?'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hssr.mmu.ac.uk/mcrh/2014/04/02/peterloo/|title=Return to Peterloo|date=2014|website=Manchester Region History Review|publisher=Manchester Centre for Regional History, MMU.|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140822231244/http://www.hssr.mmu.ac.uk/mcrh/2014/04/02/peterloo/|archivedate=22 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''.'' It will be followed by a biography of the Lancashire radical Samuel Bamford, on whom he has written several articles (some of them available online), and whose remarkable diaries he edited with Martin Hewitt for Sutton/St Martin's Press in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://uclan.academia.edu/RobertPoole|title = Robert Poole|date = 2014|accessdate = |website = academia.edu|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== Early modern England ==\nIn 2011 Poole produced a modern edition of ''The Wonderful Discovery of Witches in the County of Lancaster'' (Carnegie, 2011), the original 1612 account of the trial of the Lancashire (or Pendle) witches. <ref>{{Cite book|title = The Wonderful Discovery of Witches in the County of Lancaster|last = Poole|first = Robert|publisher = Carnegie|year = 2011|isbn = 978-1-874181-78-1|location = Lancaster|pages = }}</ref> The introduction gave the definitive account of England's biggest peacetime witch trial, summarised in an essay for the Public Domain Review.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Lancashire Witches 1612-2012|url = http://publicdomainreview.org/2012/08/22/the-lancashire-witches-1612-2012/ |website = The Public Domain Review|accessdate = 2015-06-21|date = 2012-08-22 }}</ref> He was historical adviser to the Lancashire Witches 400 commemoration programme,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://greenclose.org/new/commissions|title=Lancashire Witches 400 {{!}} Green Close|website=greenclose.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> including a long-distance walking trail featured in ''BBC History'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Lancashire Witches Walk|last=Poole|first=Dr R.|last2=Close|first2=Green|date=2013-06-04|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=9781484920718|language=English}}</ref> and to the subsequent ''Documenting Dissent'' project about prisoners of conscience at Lancaster Castle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.documentingdissent.org.uk/?page_id=16509#readmore|title=Documenting Dissent {{!}} A River of Dissent|website=www.documentingdissent.org.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> He also edited \"The [[Lancashire Witches]]: Histories and Stories\" (Manchester University Press 2002), a multidisciplinary book of essays. He has also written \"Time's Alteration: [[Calendar Reform]] In [[Early modern period|Early Modern]] England\" (UCL Press/Taylor and Francis, London, 1998), which explains the British calendar reform of 1752 and refutes the myth of riots over the missing eleven days. He explained this on the BBC Radio 4 programme 'In Our Time'.<ref name=\"test2\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00548m9 BBC Radio 4 In Our Time website]</ref> He has contributed two articles to the [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]: [[John Collier (caricaturist)|John Collier ('Tim Bobbin')]] 1708-1786, and [[William Holder]] 1616-1698). \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poole, Robert}}\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:RP 2010.jpg|thumb|Robert Poole]]  \n\n'''Robert Poole''' (born 1957) is a UK-based historian, currently Professor of History at the University of Central Lancashire, Preston.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uclan.ac.uk/staff_profiles/dr_robert_poole.php|title=Staff Profiles {{!}} About us {{!}}|website=Uclan website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827162137/http://www.uclan.ac.uk/staff_profiles/dr_robert_poole.php|archive-date=2014-08-27|url-status=dead|accessdate=2017-02-18}}</ref> He gained his PhD from the University of Lancaster in 1986, where he was associated with Prof [[Harold Perkin]]'s Centre for Social History, organising the 1996 conference of the Social History Society on 'Time and the Construction of the Past'. He has also held positions at the universities of Keele, Edge Hill and Cumbria. He has also been Leverhulme Senior Visiting Research Fellow at the University of Manchester (2000-1), an Associate of the Centre for the History of Science, Technology and Medicine, University of Manchester (2010-17), an associate of 'The Future in the Stars' research programme, Friedrich-Meinecke Institut, Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin (2012-16),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geschkult.fu-berlin.de/en/e/fmi/astrofuturismus/projekt/index.html|title=The Future in the Stars: European Astroculture and Extraterrestrial Life in the Twentieth Century. Emmy Noether research group|last=|first=|date=2012|website=The Future in the Stars: European Astroculture and Extraterrestrial Life in the Twentieth Century|publisher=Friedrich-Meinecke Institut, Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin|accessdate=}}</ref> and visiting Senior Research Fellow to the History Group, University of Hertfordshire (2013-15).\n\n== Earthrise and the space age ==\nPoole's  book \"Earthrise: How Man First Saw the Earth\" (Yale University Press, 2008),<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://yalepress.yale.edu/yupbooks/book.asp?isbn=9780300164039|title = Earthrise (paperback edition)|date = |accessdate = |website = Yale University Press|last = |first = }}</ref> a study of the first views of Earth from space and their impact, has been identified as one of the key works of the 'new aerospace history'.<ref>{{Cite book|title = To Touch the Face of God: the Sacred, the Profane and the American Space Program, 1957-1975|last = Oliver|first = Kendrick|publisher = Johns Hopkins UP|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1-4214-0788-3|location = Baltimore, Maryland|pages = 4\u20135}}</ref> He has lectured on 'Earthrise' and the cultural history of the space age in [[London, England|London]], [[Washington, D.C.]], [[Lucerne]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jesslaccetti.blogspot.co.uk/2009/07/swiss-biennial-on-science-technics.html?view=flipcard|title=[Swiss Biennial on Science, Technics + Aesthetics]|website=jesslaccetti.blogspot.co.uk|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> [[Paris, France|Paris]], [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]], and [[Copenhagen]], broadcast on American public radio networks,<ref name=\"test\">[http://www.loe.org/shows/segments.htm?programID=08-P13-00050&segmentID=6 'Living on Earth']</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://backstoryradio.org/shows/starry-eyed-heavens/|title = Starry-Eyed: a History of the Heavens|date = August 2013|website = Backstory.org|publisher = Virginia Foundation for the Humanities|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141016200652/http://backstoryradio.org/shows/starry-eyed-heavens/|archivedate = 16 October 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.npr.org/2010/02/12/123614938/an-alien-view-of-earth?ps=rs|title = Pale Blue Dot|date = Feb 2012|accessdate = |website = [[National Public Radio]] (U.S.A.)|last = |first = }}</ref> and in July 2009 wrote the op ed piece for the '[[Los Angeles Times]]' on the fortieth anniversary of the Lunar landing in July 1969 by [[Apollo 11]].<ref name=\"test4\">[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1793992381.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+19%2C+2009&author=Robert+Poole&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&edition=&startpage=A.31&desc=For+the+Apollo+crews%2C+a+small+world%3B+Traveling+to+the+moon+changed+how+they+saw+the+Earth LA Times Archive 19 July 2009]</ref> Subsequent articles have explored the science fiction writer and techno-prophet [[Arthur C. Clarke]],<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.tandfonline.com/eprint/vsU4pIysUwcTmD3Stxff/full|title = The Challenge of the Spaceship: Arthur C. Clarke and the History of the Future|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = Sep 2012|journal = History and Technology|accessdate = |doi = 10.1080/07341512.2012.722793|pmid = }}</ref> '2001: a Space Odyssey and the Dawn of Man' in the 2015 collection ''Stanley Kubrick: New Perspectives,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackdogonline.com/imported-products-2/stanley-kubrick|title=Stanley Kubrick: New Perspectives|website=Black Dog Press|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> and the myth of progress in '2001: a Space Odyssey'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9781137369154|title=Limiting Outer Space - Astroculture After Apollo {{!}} Alexander C.T. Geppert {{!}} Palgrave Macmillan|language=en}}</ref> Another recent article, 'What was Whole about the Whole Earth?', provides a missing chapter to 'Earthrise'.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Surveillance Imperative|last = Turchetti|first = Simone|publisher = Palgrave Macmillan|year = 2014|isbn = 9781137438720|location = |pages = |url = http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/the-surveillance-imperative-simone-turchetti/?k=9781137438720|last2 = Roberts|first2 = Peder}}</ref> In early 2016 he enjoyed a Short-Term Visitor Award at the [[Smithsonian Institution]], [[National Air and Space Museum]], to look at the recently-acquired papers of Arthur C. Clarke.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Arthur C. Clarke's Personal Papers Arrive at the Museum {{!}} AirSpace|url = http://blog.nasm.si.edu/highlights-from-the-collection/clarkes-personal-papers/|website = blog.nasm.si.edu|accessdate = 2015-06-21|date = 2015-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Peterloo and popular protest ==\nPoole's forthcoming book ''Peterloo: the English Uprising,'' (OUP, 2019) is an account of the 1819 [[Peterloo massacre]] in Manchester, on which he has written articles in ''Past and Present'',<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = The March to Peterloo: Politics and Festivity in Late Georgian England|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = August 2006|journal = Past and Present |volume = 192|accessdate = |doi = 10.1093/pastj/gtl006|pmid = |issue = 192|pages = 109\u2013153}}</ref> ''History'',<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = By the law or the sword: Peterloo revisited|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = April 2006|journal = History|volume = 91|accessdate = |doi = 10.1111/j.1468-229X.2006.00366.x|pmid = |issue = 302|pages = 254\u2013276}}</ref> ''Labour History Review,''<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://clok.uclan.ac.uk/6682/1/Poole%202009%20LHR.pdf|title = French revolution or peasants' revolt? Petitioners and rebels from the Blanketeers to the Chartists|last = Poole|first = Robert|date = April 2009|journal = Labour History Review|accessdate = |doi = 10.1179/174581809X408375|pmid = |issue = 74, 1}}</ref> and edited collections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchesteruniversitypress.co.uk/9780719091698/|title=Manchester University Press - Politics, performance and popular culture|work=Manchester University Press|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref> He is  historical adviser to the Peterloo 2019 commemoration programme, run jointly by Manchester Histories and the People's History Museum,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://manchesterhistories.co.uk/projects/peterloo2019|title=Peterloo 2019 - Manchester Histories|work=Manchester Histories|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> and to the  2017-18 community project by ReelMcr, 'Our Sam, Middleton man'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themeteor.org/2017/08/19/sam-middleton-man-community-needed-help-bring-middletons-famous-son-back-life/|title='Our Sam - The Middleton Man': Community needed to help bring Middleton's most famous son back to life - The Meteor|date=2017-08-19|work=The Meteor|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>He was instrumental in bringing to the John Rylands Library a full set of the radical newspaper the ''Manchester Observer'' (1818-22),  now freely available online as part of the library's Peterloo collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://luna.manchester.ac.uk/luna/servlet/Manchester~24~24|title=Peterloo Collection|website=luna.manchester.ac.uk|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> He has given numerous public lectures and workshops, including the Manchester Histories Festivals and the 2018 BBC ''Civilisations'' festival,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PeterlooMemoria|title=Peterloo Memorial (@PeterlooMemoria) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> and is an active member of the Peterloo Memorial Campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peterloomassacre.org|title=Peterloo Massacre Memorial Campaign|website=www.peterloomassacre.org|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> His broadcast appearances include ''The Matter of the North'' episode 7 'The Radical North' (BBC R4 2016),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07syyrh|title=The Radical North, The Matter of the North - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> ''Elegance and Decadence: the Age of the Regency'' episode 3 (BBC Four, 2011), ''How the North was Built'' Part 1 (ITV, 2013), ''The Real Mill'' (Channel 4, 2014),<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Real Mill with Tony Robinson|url = http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-real-mill-with-tony-robinson|website = Channel 4|accessdate = 2015-06-21}}</ref> and the BBC Schools Programme ''Exploring the Past'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Peterloo Massacre, Exploring the Past: Protest - BBC Two|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02jg2hp|website = BBC|accessdate = 2015-06-21}}</ref> He edited a volume of the Manchester Region History Review,  ''Return to Peterloo,'' contributing essays including 'What Don't We Know About Peterloo?'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hssr.mmu.ac.uk/mcrh/2014/04/02/peterloo/|title=Return to Peterloo|date=2014|website=Manchester Region History Review|publisher=Manchester Centre for Regional History, MMU.|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140822231244/http://www.hssr.mmu.ac.uk/mcrh/2014/04/02/peterloo/|archivedate=22 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''.'' It will be followed by a biography of the Lancashire radical Samuel Bamford, on whom he has written several articles (some of them available online), and whose remarkable diaries he edited with Martin Hewitt for Sutton/St Martin's Press in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://uclan.academia.edu/RobertPoole|title = Robert Poole|date = 2014|accessdate = |website = academia.edu|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== Early modern England ==\nIn 2011 Poole produced a modern edition of ''The Wonderful Discovery of Witches in the County of Lancaster'' (Carnegie, 2011), the original 1612 account of the trial of the Lancashire (or Pendle) witches. <ref>{{Cite book|title = The Wonderful Discovery of Witches in the County of Lancaster|last = Poole|first = Robert|publisher = Carnegie|year = 2011|isbn = 978-1-874181-78-1|location = Lancaster|pages = }}</ref> The introduction gave the definitive account of England's biggest peacetime witch trial, summarised in an essay for the Public Domain Review.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Lancashire Witches 1612-2012|url = http://publicdomainreview.org/2012/08/22/the-lancashire-witches-1612-2012/ |website = The Public Domain Review|accessdate = 2015-06-21|date = 2012-08-22 }}</ref> He was historical adviser to the Lancashire Witches 400 commemoration programme,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://greenclose.org/new/commissions|title=Lancashire Witches 400 {{!}} Green Close|website=greenclose.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> including a long-distance walking trail featured in ''BBC History'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Lancashire Witches Walk|last=Poole|first=Dr R.|last2=Close|first2=Green|date=2013-06-04|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=9781484920718|language=English}}</ref> and to the subsequent ''Documenting Dissent'' project about prisoners of conscience at Lancaster Castle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.documentingdissent.org.uk/?page_id=16509#readmore|title=Documenting Dissent {{!}} A River of Dissent|website=www.documentingdissent.org.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> He also edited \"The [[Lancashire Witches]]: Histories and Stories\" (Manchester University Press 2002), a multidisciplinary book of essays. He has also written \"Time's Alteration: [[Calendar Reform]] In [[Early modern period|Early Modern]] England\" (UCL Press/Taylor and Francis, London, 1998), which explains the British calendar reform of 1752 and refutes the myth of riots over the missing eleven days. He explained this on the BBC Radio 4 programme 'In Our Time'.<ref name=\"test2\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00548m9 BBC Radio 4 In Our Time website]</ref> He has contributed two articles to the [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]: [[John Collier (caricaturist)|John Collier ('Tim Bobbin')]] 1708-1786, and [[William Holder]] 1616-1698). \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poole, Robert}}\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 1 issue number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Poole_(historian)"}
{"title_page": "Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Prince Philip}}\n{{short description|Member of the British Royal Family, consort to Queen Elizabeth II}}\n{{Infobox royalty \n| consort       = yes\n| name          = Prince Philip\n| title         = [[Duke of Edinburgh]] ([[List of titles and honours of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|more]])\n| image         = 25.Jun.2015 Prince Philip in Frankfurt.jpg\n| caption       = Prince Philip in June 2015\n| succession    = [[List of British royal consorts|Consort of the British monarch]]\n| reign         = 6 February 1952&nbsp;\u2013 present\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Queen Elizabeth II]]|20 November 1947}}\n| issue-link    = #Issue\n| issue         = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n* [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\n* [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]]}}\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| house          = {{plainlist|\n*[[House of Gl\u00fccksburg|Gl\u00fccksburg]] (until 1947)\n*[[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]] (from 1947)\n*[[House of Windsor|Windsor]] (from 1947){{citation-needed|reason=\"husband doesn't belongs to wifes house on marriage by default\"|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n| father         = [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]]\n| mother         = [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]] \n| birth_name     = Prince Philip of Greece and Denmark\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1921|06|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mon Repos, Corfu|Mon Repos]], [[Corfu]],<br> [[Kingdom of Greece]]\n| signature      = Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh signature.png\n| module         = {{Infobox military person | embed=yes\n | allegiance    = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n | branch        = {{navy|United Kingdom}}<br />{{army|United Kingdom}}<br />{{air force|United Kingdom}}\n | serviceyears  = 1939\u20131952 <br />(active service)\n | rank          = [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]<br />[[Field Marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]]<br />[[Marshal of the Royal Air Force]]\n | servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records -->\n | unit          = \n | commands      = [[HMS Magpie (U82)|HMS ''Magpie'']]\n | battles_label = \n | battles       = [[Second World War]]\n*[[Battle of Crete]]\n*[[Battle of Cape Matapan]]\n*[[Allied invasion of Sicily]]\n*[[Operation Dragoon]]\n*[[Operation Robson]]\n*[[Operation Lentil (Sumatra)|Operation Lentil]]\n*[[Battle of Okinawa]]\n | awards        = {{plain list|\n* [[Mentioned in dispatches]]\n* [[Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] with Palm\n* [[Greek War Cross]]}}\n  }}\n}}\n{{British Royal Family}}\n\n'''Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh''' (born '''Prince Philip of Greece and Denmark''',<ref>[http://www.canadianheritage.gc.ca/eng/1287056173925/1297368439340 Canadian Heritage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317231641/http://www.canadianheritage.gc.ca/eng/1287056173925/1297368439340 |date=17 March 2012 }}; [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-philip/8566735/Prince-Philips-90th-birthday-a-life-less-ordinary-for-The-Duke-of-Edinburgh.html Daily Telegraph]; [http://news.sky.com/story/861428/the-life-and-times-of-the-royal-consort Sky News]; [https://www.royal.uk/the-duke-of-edinburgh Website of the Royal Family], all retrieved 10 June 2011</ref> 10 June 1921),{{#tag:ref|He was born on 10&nbsp;June 1921 according to the [[Gregorian calendar]]. Until 1&nbsp;March 1923, Greece used the [[Julian calendar]], in which the date is 28&nbsp;May 1921.|group=fn}} is the husband of [[Queen Elizabeth II]] of the [[United Kingdom]] and other [[Commonwealth realm]]s.\n\nPhilip was born into the [[Greek royal family|Greek]] and [[Danish royal family|Danish royal families]]. He was born in [[Greece]], but his family was exiled from the country when he was an infant. After being educated in France, Germany, and the United Kingdom, he joined the British [[Royal Navy]] in 1939, aged 18. From July 1939, he began corresponding with the 13-year-old Princess Elizabeth, whom he had first met in 1934. During the [[Second World War]] he served with distinction in the [[Mediterranean Fleet|Mediterranean]] and [[British Pacific Fleet|Pacific]] Fleets. After the war, Philip was granted permission by [[George VI]] to marry Elizabeth. Before the official announcement of their engagement in July 1947, he abandoned his Greek and Danish royal titles, became a naturalised [[British subject]], and adopted his maternal grandparents' surname [[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]]. He [[Wedding of Princess Elizabeth and Philip Mountbatten|married Elizabeth]] on 20 November 1947. Just before the wedding, he was created [[Duke of Edinburgh]], [[Earl of Merioneth]] and [[Baron Greenwich]]. Philip left active military service when Elizabeth became queen in 1952, having reached the rank of [[Commander (Royal Navy)|commander]], and was formally made a [[British prince]] in 1957.\n\nPhilip and Elizabeth have four children: [[Prince Charles]], [[Princess Anne]], [[Prince Andrew]], and [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]]. Through a British [[Order in Council]] issued in 1960, descendants of the couple not bearing royal styles and titles can use the surname [[Mountbatten-Windsor]], which has also been used by some members of the royal family who do hold titles, such as Princess Anne, and Princes Andrew and Edward.\n\nA keen sports enthusiast, Philip helped develop the equestrian event of [[carriage driving]]. He is a patron, president, or member of over 780 organisations, and he serves as chairman of [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] for people aged 14 to 24.<ref>{{cite web |title=Do your DofE \u2013 The Duke of Edinburgh's Award |url=https://www.dofe.org/do-your-dofe/ |website=dofe.org |accessdate=29 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129181534/https://www.dofe.org/do-your-dofe/ |archive-date=29 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is the longest-serving consort of a reigning British monarch and the oldest ever male member of the [[British royal family]]. Philip retired from his royal duties on 2 August 2017, aged 96, having completed 22,219 solo engagements since 1952.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Corfu Mon Repos R01.jpg|left|thumb|[[Mon Repos, Corfu|Mon Repos]], Philip's birthplace]]\nPrince Philip of Greece and Denmark was born in [[Mon Repos, Corfu|Mon Repos]] on the Greek island of [[Corfu]] on 10 June 1921, the only son and fifth and final child of [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]] and [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]].<ref>Brandreth, p. 56</ref> A member of the [[House of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg]], itself a branch of the [[House of Oldenburg]], he was a prince of both [[Greece]] and [[Denmark]] by virtue of his patrilineal descent from [[George I of Greece]] and [[Christian IX of Denmark]], and he was from birth in the line of succession to both thrones; the 1953 [[Act of Succession (Denmark)|Succession Act]] removed his family branch's succession rights in Denmark.<ref>{{cite book |last=T\u00e5gholt |first=Knud |year=1963 |title=Det gl\u00fccksburgske kongehus, fra Christian IX til prinsesse Margrethe:\u00a0Den danske kongesl\u00e6gt gennem hundrede \u00e5r, 1863-1963 |url= |location= |publisher=Aros |page=6 |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> Philip's four elder sisters were [[Princess Margarita of Greece and Denmark|Margarita]], [[Princess Theodora of Greece and Denmark (1906\u20131969)|Theodora]], [[Princess Cecilie of Greece and Denmark|Cecilie]], and [[Princess Sophie of Greece and Denmark|Sophie]]. He was baptised in the [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] rite at [[Old Fortress, Corfu|St. George's Church in the Old Fortress]] in Corfu.\n\nShortly after Philip's birth, his maternal grandfather, [[Prince Louis of Battenberg]], then known as Louis Mountbatten, [[Marquess of Milford Haven]], died in London. Louis was a naturalised British citizen, who, after a career in the [[Royal Navy]], had renounced his German titles and adopted the surname [[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]]\u2014an Anglicised version of [[Battenberg family|Battenberg]]\u2014during the [[World War I|First World War]], owing to [[Anti-German sentiment#First World War|anti-German sentiment]] in the United Kingdom. After visiting London for the memorial, Philip and his mother returned to Greece where Prince Andrew had remained behind to command an army division embroiled in the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u20131922)]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 58\u201359</ref>\n\nThe war went badly for Greece, and the Turks made large gains. On 22 September 1922, Philip's uncle, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine I]], was forced to abdicate and the new military government arrested Prince Andrew, along with others. The commander of the army, General [[Georgios Hatzianestis]], and five senior [[Trial of the Six|politicians were executed]]. Prince Andrew's life was believed to be in danger, and Alice was under surveillance. In December, a revolutionary court banished Prince Andrew from Greece for life.<ref>{{cite journal|title=News in Brief: Prince Andrew's Departure|journal=The Times|date=5 December 1922|page=12}}</ref> The British naval vessel [[HMS Calypso (D61)|HMS ''Calypso'']] evacuated Prince Andrew's family, with Philip carried to safety in a cot made from a fruit box. Philip's family went to France, where they settled in the Paris suburb of [[Saint-Cloud]] in a house lent to them by his wealthy aunt, [[Princess George of Greece and Denmark]].<ref>Alexandra, pp. 35\u201337; Heald, p. 31; Vickers, pp. 176\u2013178</ref>\n\nBecause Philip left Greece as a baby, he does not speak [[Greek language|Greek]]. In 1992, he said that he \"could understand a certain amount\".<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/a-strange-life-profile-of-prince-philip-1563268.html |work=The Independent |location=London |title=A strange life: Profile of Prince Philip |first=Fiammetta |last=Rocco |date=13 December 1992 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Philip has stated that he thought of himself as Danish, and his family spoke English, French, and German.<ref name=independent /> Philip, who in his youth was known for his charm, was linked to a number of women, including [[Osla Benning]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/romances-young-prince-philip/ |title=The romances of young Prince Philip |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Philip |last=Eade |date=5 May 2017 |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Youth==\n===Education===\n\n[[File:G House from the South Lawn on an Autumn Afternoon.jpg|thumb|Philip studied at [[Gordonstoun]] School, Scotland.]]\n\nPhilip was first educated at The Elms,<ref name=\"basil\">{{cite book |last1=Boothroyd |first1=Basil |title=Prince Philip: An Informal Biography |date=1971 |publisher=McCall Publishing Company |location=New York |isbn=0841501165 |edition=First American}}</ref> an American school in Paris run by Donald MacJannet, who described Philip as a \"know it all smarty person, but always remarkably polite\".<ref>Alexandra, p. 42; Heald, p. 34. Fellow pupils at the school included [[Queen Anne of Romania|Princess Anne of Bourbon-Parma]], who later married King [[Michael of Romania]].</ref> In 1928, he was sent to the United Kingdom to attend [[Cheam School]], living with his maternal grandmother, [[Victoria Mountbatten, Dowager Marchioness of Milford Haven]], at [[Kensington Palace]] and his uncle, [[George Mountbatten, 2nd Marquess of Milford Haven]], at Lynden Manor in [[Bray, Berkshire]].<ref>Heald, pp. 35\u201339</ref> In the next three years, his four sisters married German princes and moved to Germany, his mother was diagnosed with [[schizophrenia]] and placed in an asylum,<ref>Brandreth, p. 66; Vickers, p. 205</ref> and his father took up residence in [[Monte Carlo]].<ref>Eade, p. 104</ref> Philip had little contact with his mother for the remainder of his childhood.<ref>Brandreth, p. 67</ref> In 1933, he was sent to [[Schule Schloss Salem]] in Germany, which had the \"advantage of saving school fees\" because it was owned by the family of his brother-in-law, [[Berthold, Margrave of Baden]].<ref>Prince Philip quoted in Brandreth, p. 72</ref> With the rise of [[Nazism]] in Germany, Salem's Jewish founder, [[Kurt Hahn]], fled persecution and founded [[Gordonstoun]] School in Scotland, to which Philip moved after two terms at Salem.<ref>Brandreth, p. 72; Heald, p. 42</ref> In 1937, his sister [[Princess Cecilie of Greece and Denmark|Cecilie]], her husband [[Georg Donatus, Hereditary Grand Duke of Hesse]], her two young sons, [[Prince Ludwig of Hesse and by Rhine|Ludwig]] and [[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine (1933\u20131937)|Alexander]], her newborn infant, and her mother-in-law, [[Princess Eleonore of Solms-Hohensolms-Lich]], were killed in [[Sabena OO-AUB Ostend crash|an air crash at Ostend]]; Philip, then 16 years old, attended the funeral in [[Darmstadt]].<ref>Brandreth, p. 69; Vickers, p. 273</ref><!--also in Heald--> The following year, his uncle and guardian Lord Milford Haven died of [[bone marrow cancer]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 77, 136<!--Heald says cancer but does not specify--></ref>\n\n===Naval and wartime service===\n[[File:HMS Valiant-2.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Philip served aboard {{HMS|Valiant|1914|6}} in the [[Battle of the Mediterranean]]]]\nAfter leaving Gordonstoun in early 1939, Philip completed a term as a cadet at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], then repatriated to Greece, living with his mother in Athens for a month in mid-1939. At the behest of the Greek king, [[George II of Greece|George II]], he returned to Britain in September to resume training for the [[Royal Navy]].<ref>Eade, pp. 129\u2013130; Vickers, pp. 284\u2013285, 433.</ref> He graduated from Dartmouth the next year as the best cadet in his course.<ref name=royalgov>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Navalcareer.aspx |title=Naval career |publisher=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=7 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529132154/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Navalcareer.aspx |archivedate=29 May 2010}}</ref> During the Second World War, he continued to serve in the British forces, while two of his brothers-in-law, [[Prince Christoph of Hesse]] and [[Berthold, Margrave of Baden]], fought on the opposing German side.<ref>Vickers, pp. 293\u2013295.</ref> Philip was appointed as a midshipman in January 1940. He spent four months on the battleship {{HMS|Ramillies|07|6}}, protecting convoys of the [[Second Australian Imperial Force|Australian Expeditionary Force]] in the Indian Ocean, followed by shorter postings on {{HMS|Kent|54|6}}, on {{HMS|Shropshire|73|6}}, and in [[Ceylon]].<ref>Eade, pp. 132\u2013133.</ref> After the [[Greco-Italian War|invasion of Greece by Italy]] in October 1940, he was transferred from the Indian Ocean to the battleship {{HMS|Valiant|1914|6}} in the [[Mediterranean Fleet (United Kingdom)|Mediterranean Fleet]].<ref>Heald, p. 60.</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 1941,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35455|date=13 February 1942 |page=715 |supp= |nolink=y}}</ref> Philip was commissioned as a sub-lieutenant after a series of courses at [[Portsmouth]], in which he gained the top grade in four out of five sections of the qualifying examination.<ref>Brandreth, p. 154; Heald, p. 66.</ref> Among other engagements, he was involved in the [[battle of Crete]], and was [[mentioned in dispatches]] for his service during the [[battle of Cape Matapan]],<ref name=\"basil\" /> in which he controlled the battleship's searchlights. He was also awarded the [[Greek War Cross]] of Valour.<ref name=royalgov /> In June 1942, he was appointed to the [[V and W-class destroyer]] and flotilla leader [[Thornycroft type leader|HMS ''Wallace'']], which was involved in convoy escort tasks on the east coast of Britain, as well as the [[Allied invasion of Sicily]].<ref name=\"smith\">{{cite web| last=Smith| first=David| title=Prince Philip's war heroics come to light after 60 years| newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 December 2003| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/28/monarchy.davidsmith| accessdate=12 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nPromotion to lieutenant followed on 16 July 1942.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35664|date=11 August 1942 |page=3510 |supp=|nolink=y}}</ref> In October of the same year, he became first lieutenant of HMS ''Wallace'', at 21 years old one of the youngest first lieutenants in the Royal Navy. During the invasion of Sicily, in July 1943, as second in command of ''Wallace'', he saved his ship from a night bomber attack. He devised a plan to launch a raft with smoke floats that successfully distracted the bombers, allowing the ship to slip away unnoticed.<ref name=\"smith\"/> In 1944, he moved on to the new destroyer, {{HMS|Whelp|R37|6}}, where he saw service with the [[British Pacific Fleet]] in the 27th Destroyer Flotilla.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 155\u2013163; Heald, pp. 66\u201367.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/xGM-Chrono-10DD-63W-Whelp.htm |title=HMS Whelp, destroyer |publisher=Naval-history.net |accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> He was present in [[Tokyo Bay]] when the instrument of [[Japanese surrender]] was signed. Philip returned to the United Kingdom on the ''Whelp'' in January 1946, and was posted as an instructor at {{HMS|Royal Arthur|shore establishment|6}}, the Petty Officers' School in [[Corsham]], Wiltshire.<ref>Brandreth, p. 176.</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\n{{further|Wedding of Princess Elizabeth and Philip Mountbatten}}\n[[File:Royal Monogram of Prince Philip of Great Britain.svg|thumb|upright|Philip's monogram]]\nIn 1939, [[King George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] toured the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]]. During the visit, the Queen and [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]] asked Philip to escort the King's two daughters, [[Elizabeth II|Elizabeth]] and [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Margaret]], who were Philip's [[Royal descendants of Queen Victoria and King Christian IX#Monarchs descended from Queen Victoria|third cousins]] through [[Queen Victoria]], and [[Royal descendants of Queen Victoria and King Christian IX#Monarchs descended from King Christian IX|second cousins once removed]] through [[King Christian IX of Denmark]].<ref>[[Alexandra of Yugoslavia|Queen Alexandra of Yugoslavia]] quoted in Heald, p. 57</ref> Elizabeth fell in love with Philip, and they began to exchange letters when she was 13.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 132\u2013136, 166\u2013168</ref>\n\nEventually, in the summer of 1946, Philip asked the King for his daughter's hand in marriage. The King granted his request, provided that any formal engagement be delayed until Elizabeth's 21st birthday the following April.<ref>Brandreth, p. 183</ref> By March 1947, Philip had abandoned his Greek and Danish royal titles, had adopted the surname [[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]] from his mother's family, and had become a naturalised British subject. The engagement was announced to the public on 10 July 1947.<ref>Heald, p. 77</ref>\n\nThough Philip appeared \"always to have regarded himself as an Anglican\",<ref>''The Times'', 10 July 1947, p. 4</ref> and he had attended Anglican services with his classmates and relations in England and throughout his Royal Navy days, he had been baptised in the Greek Orthodox Church. The [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Geoffrey Fisher]], wanted to \"regularise\" Philip's position by officially receiving him into the Church of England,<ref>{{cite book |author=Boothroyd, Basil |authorlink=Basil Boothroyd |year=1971 |title=Prince Philip: An Informal Biography |publisher=McCall |isbn=0841501165 |pages=45\u201347}}</ref> which he did in October 1947.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1947/10/04/archives/elizabeths-fiance-now-an-anglican.html \"Elizabeth's Fiance Now an Anglican\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'', 4 October 1947</ref>\n\nThe day before the wedding, King George VI bestowed the [[Style (manner of address)|style]] of ''[[Royal Highness]]'' on Philip and, on the morning of the wedding, 20 November 1947, he was made the [[Duke of Edinburgh]], [[Earl of Merioneth]], and [[Baron Greenwich]] of Greenwich in the County of London.<ref name=\"LG 21 Nov 1947\">{{London Gazette |issue=38128 |pages=5495\u20135496 |date=21 November 1947}}</ref> Consequently, being already a [[Knight of the Garter]], between 19 and 20 November 1947 he bore the unusual style His Royal Highness Sir Philip Mountbatten, and is so described in the [[Letters Patent]] of 20 November 1947.<ref name=\"LG 21 Nov 1947\"/>\n\nPhilip and Elizabeth were married in a ceremony at [[Westminster Abbey]], recorded and broadcast by [[BBC]] radio to 200&nbsp;million people around the world.<ref>Heald, p. 86</ref> In post-war Britain it was not acceptable for any of the Duke of Edinburgh's German relations to be invited to the wedding, including Philip's three surviving sisters, all of whom had married German princes. After their marriage, the Duke and Duchess of Edinburgh took up residence at [[Clarence House]]. Their first two children were born before Elizabeth succeeded her father as monarch in 1952:  [[Prince Charles]] in 1948 and [[Princess Anne]] in 1950. Their marriage is now the longest of any British monarch.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7101094.stm |title=Queen celebrates diamond wedding |date=19 November 2007 |accessdate=10 February 2017 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/9689130/Queen-and-Duke-of-Edinburgh-celebrate-65th-wedding-anniversary.html |title=Queen and Duke of Edinburgh celebrate 65th wedding anniversary |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=19 November 2012 |accessdate=10 February 2017 |first=Gordon |last=Rayner}}</ref>\n\nPhilip was introduced to the [[House of Lords]] on 21 July 1948,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh |title=HRH The Duke of Edinburgh (Lords Sitting of 21 July 1948) |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820064849/https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh |archive-date=20 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> immediately before his uncle Louis Mountbatten, who had been made [[Earl Mountbatten of Burma]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/earl-mountbatten-of-burma |title=Earl Mountbatten of Burma (Lords Sitting of 21 July 1948) |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820064857/https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/earl-mountbatten-of-burma |archive-date=20 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Philip, like his sons Charles and Andrew and other royals (with the exception of the [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|1st Earl of Snowdon]]), ceased to be members of the House of Lords following the [[House of Lords Act 1999]]. He never spoke in the House.\n\n[[File:Princess Elizabeth, Prince Philip and Louis St. Laurent.jpg|thumb|1951 tour of Canada with Prime Minister [[Louis St. Laurent]]]]\nAfter his honeymoon at the Mountbatten family home, [[Broadlands]], Philip returned to the navy at first in a desk job at [[the Admiralty]], and later on a staff course at the [[Royal Naval College (Greenwich)|Naval Staff College, Greenwich]].<ref>Alexandra, pp. 100, 105\u2013106</ref> From 1949, he was stationed in [[Malta]] (residing at [[Villa Guardamangia]]) after being posted as the first lieutenant of the destroyer [[HMS Chequers (R61)|HMS ''Chequers'']], the lead ship of the 1st Destroyer Flotilla in the Mediterranean Fleet.<ref>Heald, p. 94</ref> On 16 July 1950, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant commander (Royal Navy)|lieutenant commander]] and given command of the frigate [[HMS Magpie (U82)|HMS ''Magpie'']].<ref>Heald, p. 95</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38994 |supp=y |page=4152 |date=15 August 1950}}</ref> On 30 June 1952, Philip was promoted to [[Commander (Royal Navy)|commander]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39597 |supp= |page=3821 |date=15 July 1952}}</ref> though his active naval career had ended in July 1951.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Militaryinvolvement.aspx |title=The Duke of Edinburgh > Military involvement |publisher=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=7 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528151405/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Militaryinvolvement.aspx |archivedate=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Heald, p. 97</ref>\n\nWith the King in ill health, Princess Elizabeth and the Duke of Edinburgh were both appointed to the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] on 4 November 1951, after a coast-to-coast tour of [[Canada]]. At the end of January 1952, Philip and his wife set out on a tour of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]]. On 6 February 1952, they were in [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]] when Elizabeth's father died and she became queen. It was Philip who broke the news to Elizabeth at [[Sagana Lodge]], and the royal party immediately returned to the United Kingdom.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 245\u2013247</ref>\n\n==Consort of the Queen==\n===Royal house===\n\n[[File:Elizabeth and Philip 1953.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Coronation of Elizabeth II|Coronation]] portrait of Elizabeth II with the Duke of Edinburgh, June 1953]]\nThe accession of Elizabeth to the throne brought up the question of the name of the [[royal house]], as Elizabeth would typically have taken Philip's last name upon marriage. The Duke's uncle, Earl Mountbatten of Burma, advocated the name ''House of Mountbatten''. Philip suggested ''House of Edinburgh'', after his ducal title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/9305749/Emma-Soames-As-Churchills-were-proud-to-do-our-duty.html|title=Emma Soames: As Churchills we're proud to do our duty|last=Soames|first=Emma|date=2012-06-01|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> When [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]], Elizabeth's grandmother, heard of this, she informed the British prime minister, [[Winston Churchill]], who himself later advised the Queen to issue a royal proclamation declaring that the royal house was to remain known as the [[House of Windsor]]. Prince Philip privately complained, \"I am nothing but a bloody amoeba. I am the only man in the country not allowed to give his name to his own children.\"<ref>Brandreth, pp. 253\u2013254</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 1960, several years after the death of Queen Mary and the resignation of Churchill as prime minister, the Queen issued an [[Order in Council]] declaring that [[Mountbatten-Windsor]] would be the surname of her and her husband's male-line descendants who are not styled as Royal Highness or titled as prince or princess.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41948/supplement/1003 |work=[[The London Gazette]] |title=Supplement to The London Gazette of Friday, 5th February 1960 |date=8 February 1960}}</ref> While it seems the Queen had \"absolutely set her heart\" on such a change and had it in mind for some time, it occurred only 11 days before the birth of [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Prince Andrew]] (19 February), and only after three months of protracted correspondence between constitutional expert [[Edward Iwi]] (who averred that, without such a change, the royal child would be born with \"the Badge of Bastardy\") and Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]] who had attempted to rebuff Iwi.<ref>Travis, Alan (18 February 1999). [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/feb/18/monarchy \"Queen feared 'slur' on family\", ''The Guardian'']. Retrieved 17 April 2014</ref>\n\nAfter her accession to the throne, the Queen also announced that the Duke was to have \"place, pre-eminence and precedence\" next to her \"on all occasions and in all meetings, except where otherwise provided by [[Act of Parliament]]\". This meant the Duke took precedence over his son, the [[Prince of Wales]], except, officially, in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British parliament]]. In fact, however, he attends Parliament only when escorting the Queen for the annual [[State Opening of Parliament]], where he walks and sits beside her.<ref>British-Japanese Parliamentary Group. [https://web.archive.org/web/20130603102831/http://www.bjpg.co.uk/publications/Tour_of_Parliament_(English).pdf Tour of the Palace of Westminster]. Retrieved 2012/5/2.</ref> Contrary to rumours over the years, the Queen and Duke are said by insiders to have had a strong relationship throughout their marriage, despite the challenges of Elizabeth's reign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Love and Majesty |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/society/2012/01/queen-elizabeth-201201 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"itv\"/> The Queen referred to Prince Philip in a speech on the occasion of her Diamond Jubilee in 2012 as her \"constant strength and guide\".<ref name=\"itv\">{{cite news |title=Prince Philip: The Man At The Queen's Side |date=5 June 2012 |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2012-06-05/prince-philip-the-man-at-the-queens-side/ |publisher=ITV}}</ref>\n\nPrince Philip receives a Parliamentary annuity (of \u00a3359,000 since 1990{{#tag:ref|The amount was set by the Civil List (Increase of Financial Provision) Order 1990. It was initially set at \u00a340,000 in the Civil List Act 1952, raised to \u00a365,000 by the Civil List Act 1972, and raised to \u00a3165,000 by the Civil List (Increase of Financial Provision) Order 1984.|group=fn}}) that serves to meet official expenses in carrying out public duties. The annuity is unaffected by the reform of royal finances under the [[Sovereign Grant Act 2011]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Royal Public Finances |url=https://www.royal.gov.uk/pdf/Introduction%20to%20Head%20of%20State%20expenditure%202006-07.pdf |accessdate=7 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224234303/https://www.royal.gov.uk/pdf/Introduction%20to%20Head%20of%20State%20expenditure%202006-07.pdf |archivedate=24 February 2014}}</ref><ref>\"Living off the State, A critical guide to UK Royal Finance\", Jon Temple, 2nd edition 2012</ref> Any part of the allowance that is not used to meet official expenditure is liable for tax. In practice, the entire allowance is used to fund his official duties.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sovereign grant Act 2011: Tax |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sovereign-grant-act-2011-guidance/sovereign-grant-act-2011-guidance#tax |accessdate=7 August 2014 |publisher=www.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Duties and milestones===\n[[File:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, Cambridge, Waikato (January 1 1954) (17843185594).jpg|thumb|upright|In [[Cambridge, New Zealand]] 1954]]\n\nAs consort to the Queen, Philip supported his wife in her new duties as sovereign, accompanying her to ceremonies such as the [[State Opening of Parliament]] in various countries, state dinners, and tours abroad. As chairman of the [[Coronation of the British monarch|Coronation]] Commission, he was the first member of the royal family to fly in a helicopter, visiting the troops that were to take part in the ceremony.<ref>Brandreth, p. 259</ref> Philip was not crowned in the service, but knelt before Elizabeth, with her hands enclosing his, and swore to be her \"liege man of life and limb\".<ref>Brandreth, p. 263</ref>\n[[File:Prince Philip and Elizabeth II, 1954.jpg|left|thumb|In [[Queensland]], Australia, 1954]]\nIn the early 1950s, his sister-in-law, [[Princess Margaret]], considered marrying a divorced older man, [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]]. The press accused Philip of being hostile to the match, to which he replied \"I haven't done anything.\" Philip had not interfered, preferring to stay out of other people's love lives.<ref>Brandreth, p. 270</ref> Eventually, Margaret and Townsend parted. For six months, over 1953\u201354, Philip and Elizabeth toured the Commonwealth; as with previous tours the children were left in Britain.<ref>Brandreth, p. 278</ref>\n\nIn 1956, the Duke, with [[Kurt Hahn]], founded [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] in order to give young people \"a sense of responsibility to themselves and their communities\". In the same year, he also established the [[Commonwealth Study Conference]]s. From 1956 to 1957, Philip travelled around the world aboard the newly commissioned [[HMY Britannia|HMY ''Britannia'']], during which he opened the [[1956 Summer Olympics]] in Melbourne and visited the [[Antarctica|Antarctic]], becoming the first royal to cross the [[Antarctic Circle]].<ref name=\"royanikkhah\">{{cite web|last1=Nikkhah|first1=Roya|title=Prince Philip: The Duke you don't know|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/8273569/Prince-Philip-the-Duke-you-dont-know.html|website=The Telegraph (UK)|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> The Queen and the children remained in the UK. On the return leg of the journey, Philip's private secretary, [[Michael Parker (courtier)|Mike Parker]], was sued for divorce by his wife. As with Townsend, the press still portrayed divorce as a scandal and eventually Parker resigned. He later said that the Duke was very supportive and \"the Queen was wonderful throughout. She regarded divorce as a sadness, not a hanging offence.\"<ref>Quoted in Brandreth, p. 287</ref> In a public show of support, the Queen created Parker a Commander of the [[Royal Victorian Order]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 287, 289</ref>\n\nFurther press reports claimed that the Queen and the Duke were drifting apart, which enraged the Duke and dismayed the Queen, who issued a strongly worded denial.<ref>Brandreth, p. 288</ref> On 22 February 1957, she granted her husband the style and title of a Prince of the United Kingdom by [[Letters Patent]], and it was gazetted that he was to be known as \"His Royal Highness The Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh\".<ref name=\"prince\">{{London Gazette |issue=41009 |date=22 February 1957 |page=1209}}</ref> Philip was appointed to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] on 14 October 1957, taking his [[Oath of Allegiance (Canada)|Oath of Allegiance]] before the Queen in person at her Canadian residence, [[Rideau Hall]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bousfield |first=Arthur |author2=Toffoli, Gary |title=Fifty Years the Queen |publisher=Dundurn Press |year=2002 |location=Toronto |page=12 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=w8l5reK7NjoC&printsec=frontcover&q= |isbn=1-55002-360-8}}</ref> Remarks he made two years later to the [[Canadian Medical Association]] on the subject of youth and sport were taken as a suggestion that Canadian children were out of shape. This was at first considered \"tactless\", but Philip was later admired for his encouragement of physical fitness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/prince-philip-hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh/ |title=Prince Philip (HRH The Duke of Edinburgh) |work=The Canadian Encyclopedia |publisher=Historica Canada |accessdate=23 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609155631/http://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/prince-philip-hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh/ |archive-date=9 June 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Canada in 1969, Philip spoke about his views on republicanism:\n{{Quote|It is a complete misconception to imagine that the monarchy exists in the interests of the monarch. It doesn't. It exists in the interests of the people. If at any time any nation decides that the system is unacceptable, then it is up to them to change it.<ref>Brandreth, p. 50</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, at Salford University in 1967.jpg|thumb|Visiting Salford University in 1967]]\n\nPhilip is [[Patronage|patron]] of some 800 organisations, particularly focused on the environment, industry, sport, and education. His first solo engagement as Duke of Edinburgh was in March 1948, presenting prizes at the boxing finals of the London Federation of Boys' Clubs at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke of Edinburgh attended boxing match as first of 22,000 official duties |url=https://www.metro.news/philip-attended-boxing-match-as-first-of-22000-official-solo-engagements/695455/ |website=Metro News |access-date=23 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124041504/https://www.metro.news/philip-attended-boxing-match-as-first-of-22000-official-solo-engagements/695455/ |archive-date=24 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was president of the [[National Playing Fields Association]] (now known as [[Fields in Trust]]) for 64 years, from 1947 until his grandson Prince William took over the role in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince William succeeds the Duke of Edinburgh as he gives up royal role|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/390492/Prince-William-succeeds-the-Duke-of-Edinburgh-as-he-gives-up-royal-role|accessdate=7 December 2016|work=Daily Express|date=9 April 2013}}</ref> He served as UK president of the [[World Wildlife Fund]] from 1961 to 1982, international president from 1981, and president emeritus from 1996.<ref name=\"royanikkhah\" /> In 1952, he became patron of The Industrial Society (since renamed [[The Work Foundation]]).<ref name=\"basil\" /> He was president of the [[International Equestrian Federation]] from 1964 to 1986,<ref name=\"equestrianfederation\">{{cite web|title=Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, Talks Love of and Involvement in Combined Driving|url=https://www.usequestrian.org/media/press-releases/prince-philip-duke-of-edinburgh-talks-love-of-involvement-in-combined-driving-in-first-post-retirement-interview-at-royal-windsor-horse-show|website=US Equestrian|publisher=US Equestrian Communications Department|accessdate=12 December 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212152435/https://www.usequestrian.org/media/press-releases/prince-philip-duke-of-edinburgh-talks-love-of-involvement-in-combined-driving-in-first-post-retirement-interview-at-royal-windsor-horse-show|archivedate=12 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has served as chancellor of the universities of Cambridge, [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], [[University of Salford|Salford]], and [[University of Wales|Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Activitiesandinterests.aspx |title=The Duke of Edinburgh: Activities and interests |publisher=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106114941/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Activitiesandinterests.aspx |archivedate=6 November 2011 }}</ref> In 2017, the [[British Heart Foundation]] thanked Prince Philip for being its patron for 55 years, during which time, in addition to organising fundraisers, he \"supported the creation of nine BHF-funded centres of excellence\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Chief Executive thanks Prince Philip for his commitment as Patron|url=https://www.bhf.org.uk/news-from-the-bhf/news-archive/2017/may/our-chief-executive-thanks-prince-philip-for-his-work-as-patron|website=News Archive|publisher=British Heart Foundation|accessdate=30 December 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230024120/https://www.bhf.org.uk/news-from-the-bhf/news-archive/2017/may/our-chief-executive-thanks-prince-philip-for-his-work-as-patron|archivedate=30 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is an Honorary Fellow of [[St Edmund's College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/people/hrh-prince-philip-duke-edinburgh|title=St Edmund's College \u2013 University of Cambridge|website=www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910204442/http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/people/hrh-prince-philip-duke-edinburgh|archive-date=10 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Charles and Diana====\n[[File:Duke of Edinburgh 33 Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|upright|Philip in 1992]]\n\nAt the beginning of 1981, Philip wrote to his eldest son, Charles, counselling him to make up his mind to either propose to [[Lady Diana Spencer]] or break off their courtship.<ref>Brandreth, p. 344; Lacey, p. 276</ref> Charles felt pressured by his father to make a decision and did so, proposing to Diana in February.<ref>Brandreth, p. 346; Lacey, pp. 277\u2013278</ref> [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Lady Diana Spencer|They married]] five months later. By 1992, the marriage of the Prince and Princess of Wales had broken down. The Queen and Philip hosted a meeting between Charles and Diana, trying to effect a reconciliation, but without success.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 348\u2013349</ref> Philip wrote to Diana, expressing his disappointment at both Charles's and her extra-marital affairs, and asking her to examine both his and her behaviour from the other's point of view.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 349\u2013351</ref> She found the letters hard to take, but nevertheless appreciated that he was acting with good intent.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 351\u2013353</ref> Charles and Diana separated and later divorced.\n\nA year after the divorce, [[Death of Diana, Princess of Wales|Diana was killed in a car crash]] in Paris on 31 August 1997. At the time, the Duke was on holiday at Balmoral with the extended royal family. In their grief, Diana's two sons, Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry|Harry]], wanted to attend church and so their grandparents took them that morning.<ref name=brandreth1>Brandreth, p. 358</ref> For five days, the Queen and the Duke shielded their grandsons from the ensuing press interest by keeping them at Balmoral, where they could grieve in private.<ref name=\"brandreth1\" /> The royal family's seclusion caused public dismay,<ref name=\"brandreth1\" /> but the public mood changed after a live broadcast made by the Queen on 5&nbsp;September.<ref name=\"brandreth2\">Brandreth, p. 359</ref> Uncertain as to whether they should walk behind her coffin during the [[Funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales|funeral procession]], Diana's sons hesitated.<ref name=\"brandreth2\" /> Philip told William, \"If you don't walk, I think you'll regret it later. If I walk, will you walk with me?\"<ref name=\"brandreth2\" /> On the day of the funeral, Philip, William, Harry, Charles, and Diana's brother, [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Earl Spencer]], walked through London behind her bier.\n\nOver the next few years, [[Mohamed Fayed]], whose son [[Dodi Fayed]] was also killed in the crash, claimed that Prince Philip had ordered the death of Diana and that the accident was staged. The inquest into the Princess of Wales's death concluded in 2008 that there was no evidence of a conspiracy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7322204.stm |work=BBC News |title=Duke 'did not order Diana death' |date=31 March 2008 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====21st century====\nDuring [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|his wife's Golden Jubilee]] in 2002, the Duke was commended by the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the British House of Commons]] for his role in supporting the Queen during her reign. The Duke of Edinburgh's time as royal consort exceeds that of any other consort in British history;<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince Philip reaches milestone |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8005464.stm |accessdate=7 June 2013 |work=BBC News |date=18 April 2009}}</ref> however, [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] (his mother-in-law), who died aged 101, has had the longest lifespan to date. Philip is also the oldest ever male member of the British royal family, and the third longest-lived following [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]], and Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-04-19/philip-becomes-third-oldest-royal-in-british-history/|title=Prince Philip, 97, becomes third oldest royal (and oldest ever male) in British history - but who is number one?|publisher=ITV News|date=19 April 2019|accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, 2006.jpg|thumb|left|Philip in 2006]]\n\nIn April 2008, Philip was admitted to [[King Edward VII's Hospital]], London, for \"assessment and treatment\" for a chest infection, though he walked into the hospital unaided and recovered quickly,<ref>{{cite web| title=Duke of Edinburgh is in hospital|publisher=BBC News| date=4 April 2008| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7333280.stm| accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> and was discharged three days later to recuperate at [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Prince discharged from hospital|publisher=BBC News| date=6 April 2008| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7330697.stm| accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> In August, the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' reported that he was suffering from [[prostate cancer]]. Buckingham Palace, which usually refuses to comment on rumours of ill health, claimed that the report was an invasion of privacy and issued a statement denying the story.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement From Buckingham Palace Following the Evening Standard's Story Entitled 'Prince Philip Defies Cancer Scare' |publisher=Buckingham Palace |date=6 August 2008 |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2008/STATEMENTFROMBUCKINGHAMPALACEFOLLOWINGTHEEVENINGST.aspx |accessdate=20 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202213153/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2008/STATEMENTFROMBUCKINGHAMPALACEFOLLOWINGTHEEVENINGST.aspx |archivedate=2 December 2010 }}</ref> The newspaper retracted the report and admitted it was untrue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/08/08/british-paper-retracts-story-claiming-prince-philip-has-prostate-cancer/|title=British Paper Retracts Story Claiming Prince Philip Has Prostate Cancer|publisher=Fox News|date=8 August 2008|access-date=1 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110040853/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/08/08/british-paper-retracts-story-claiming-prince-philip-has-prostate-cancer/|archive-date=10 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.smh.com.au/world/paper-apologises-for-prince-philip-story-20080808-3sea.html|title=Paper apologises for Prince Philip story|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, in an interview marking his 90th birthday he said that he would now slow down and reduce his duties, stating that he had \"done [his] bit\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Prince Philip Turns 90 and Vows to 'Slow Down'|publisher=BBC News| date=10 June 2011| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13722857| accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref> His wife, the Queen, gave him the title [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]] for his 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13730067 |title=New title for Duke of Edinburgh as he turns 90 |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2011 |accessdate=10 June 2011}}</ref> While staying at [[Sandringham House]], the royal residence in Norfolk, on 23 December 2011, the Duke suffered chest pains and was taken to the cardio-thoracic unit at [[Papworth Hospital]], Cambridgeshire, where he underwent successful [[Percutaneous coronary intervention|coronary angioplasty]] and [[Coronary stent|stenting]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Peter Hunt |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16323794 |title=Prince Philip has heart procedure at Papworth Hospital |publisher=BBC News|date=24 December 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref> He was discharged on 27 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-16337357|title=Duke of Edinburgh leaves hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=27 December 2011|accessdate=27 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HM The Queen and Prince Philip.JPG|thumb|On the balcony of [[Buckingham Palace]], 2012]]\n\nOn 4 June 2012, during the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|celebrations]] in honour of his wife's [[Diamond Jubilee]], Philip was taken from Windsor Castle to King Edward VII's Hospital suffering from a bladder infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itn.co.uk/home/46928/Duke+of+Edinburgh+hospitalised|title=Duke of Edinburgh hospitalised|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012|publisher=[[ITN]]}}{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Philip in hospital and to miss Diamond Jubilee concert|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18325522|work=BBC News|accessdate=4 June 2012|date=4 June 2012}}</ref> He was released from hospital on 9 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/09/world/europe/uk-prince-philip/index.html?hpt=hp_t2|title=Britain's Prince Philip released from hospital in time for his birthday|publisher=CNN|date=9 June 2012}}</ref> After a recurrence of infection in August 2012, while staying at [[Balmoral Castle]], he was admitted to [[Aberdeen Royal Infirmary]] for five nights as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19317991|title=Prince Philip leaves Aberdeen hospital after five nights|work=BBC News|date=20 August 2012}}</ref> In June 2013, Philip was admitted to the [[London Clinic]] for an [[Exploratory surgery|exploratory operation]] on his abdomen, spending 11 days in hospital.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Philip leaves hospital, will recuperate at Windsor Castle|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/17/world/europe/uk-prince-philip-hospital/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=17 June 2013|date=17 June 2013}}</ref> On 21 May 2014, the Prince appeared in public with a bandage on his right hand after a \"minor procedure\" was performed in Buckingham Palace the preceding day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Duke of Edinburgh has 'minor procedure' on hand|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-27507555|accessdate=7 August 2014|work=BBC News|date=21 May 2014}}</ref> In June 2017, he was taken from Windsor to London and admitted to King Edward VII's Hospital after being diagnosed with an infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/21/duke-edinburgh-admitted-hospital-infection/|title=Prince Philip admitted to hospital with infection and misses State Opening of Parliament|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Hannah|last=Furness|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref> He spent two nights in the hospital and was unable to attend the State Opening of Parliament and Royal Ascot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/21/prince-philip-admitted-to-hospital-with-infection|title=Prince Philip to spend second night in hospital|work=The Guardian|first=Caroline|last=Davies|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/22/europe/prince-philip-discharged-hospital/index.html|title=UK's Prince Philip Discharged from Hospital after Treatment for Infection|publisher=CNN|first=Eliza|last=Mackintosh|date=22 June 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nPrince Philip retired from his royal duties on 2 August 2017, meeting Royal Marines in his final solo public engagement, aged 96. Since 1952 he had completed 22,219 solo engagements. Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] thanked him for \"a remarkable lifetime of service\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/prince-philip-prepares-for-final-royal-engagement-10970314|title=Prince Philip carries out final royal engagement before retirement|date=2 August 2017|publisher=Sky News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40798469|title=Prince Philip carries out final official engagement|work=BBC News|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> On 20 November 2017, he celebrated his 70th wedding anniversary with the Queen, which made her the first British monarch to celebrate a platinum wedding anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/nov/20/queen-prince-philip-portraits-platinum-wedding-70th-anniversary|title=Queen and Prince Philip portraits released to mark 70th anniversary|date=20 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2018, Philip was admitted to King Edward VII's Hospital for a planned [[hip replacement]], which took place the next day. This came after the Duke missed the annual Maundy and Easter Sunday services. On 12 April his daughter, Princess Anne, spent about 50 minutes in the hospital and afterwards said her father was \"on good form\". He was discharged the following day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43755269|title=Duke of Edinburgh leaves hospital|date=13 April 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=13 April 2018}}</ref> On 19 May, six weeks later, he attended the [[Wedding of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle|wedding]] of his grandson Prince Harry to [[Meghan Markle]] and was able to walk with the Queen unaided.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cpwpy79d6dxt/royal-wedding-2018|title=Royal Wedding 2018|website=BBC News|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref> That October, he accompanied the Queen to the [[Wedding of Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank|wedding]] of their granddaughter [[Princess Eugenie]] to [[Jack Brooksbank]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/in-pictures-45829410|title=Princess Eugenie wedding in pictures: Splendid hats and gusts of wind|work=BBC News|date=12 October 2018}}</ref> with ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reporting that Philip works on a \"wake up and see how I feel\" basis when deciding whether to attend an event or not.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2018/10/09/duke-edinburgh-will-decide-day-attends-royal-wedding/|title=Duke of Edinburgh 'will decide at last moment' whether he attends royal wedding of Princess Eugenie|work=The Telegraph|first=Camilla|last=Tominey|date=9 October 2018|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2019, 97-year-old Philip was involved in a car crash as he pulled out onto a main road near the [[Sandringham Estate]]. An official statement said he was uninjured. An eyewitness who came to the prince's aid described having to wipe blood off his hands.<ref name=\"furness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/01/18/road-prince-philip-crashed-expected-have-speed-limit-reduced/|title=Prince Philip crash: Duke 'asked if everyone else was alright' after car 'tumbled' across road leaving him bleeding|date=18 January 2019|accessdate=18 January 2019|author=Hannah Furness|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> The driver and a passenger of the other car were injured and taken to hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jan/20/prince-philip-has-not-said-sorry-for-car-crash-injured-woman-claims|title=Prince Philip has not said sorry for car crash, injured woman claims|author=Haroon Siddique|date=20 January 2019|accessdate=20 January 2019|website=The Guardian}}</ref> Philip attended hospital the next morning as a precaution.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jan/18/prince-philip-car-crash-norfolk-police-to-investigate|title=Prince Philip undergoes hospital checks after car crash|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2019|author=Caroline Davies|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He apologised,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/01/27/prince-philip-apologises-mother-involved-car-crash/|title=Prince Philip sends personal apology to victims of Sandringham car crash|website=The Telegraph|date=27 January 2019|accessdate=9 February 2019|author=Victoria Ward}}</ref> and three weeks later voluntarily surrendered his driving licence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/feb/09/prince-philip-surrenders-his-driving-licence|title=Prince Philip gives up driving licence three weeks after car crash|date=9 February 2019|accessdate=9 February 2019|website=The Guardian|author=Lin Jenkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47186875|title=Prince Philip, 97, gives up driving licence|publisher=BBC|date=9 February 2019|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> On 14 February the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced that prosecuting Philip would not be in the public interest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/feb/14/prince-philip-will-not-be-prosecuted-over-car-crash-cps|title=Prince Philip will not be prosecuted over car crash, says CPS|date=14 February 2019|accessdate=14 February 2019|website=The Guardian|author=Owen Bowcott}}</ref> The Duke is still allowed to drive around private estates, and was seen behind the wheel in the grounds of Windsor Castle in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/prince-philip-spotted-behind-wheel-for-first-time-since-giving-up-licence-918660.html|title=Prince Philip 'spotted behind wheel for first time since giving up licence'|newspaper=Irish Examiner|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=19 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418181509/https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/prince-philip-spotted-behind-wheel-for-first-time-since-giving-up-licence-918660.html|archive-date=18 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 20\u201324 December 2019, Philip stayed at King Edward VII's Hospital, in a visit described by Buckingham Palace as a \"precautionary measure\". He had not been seen in public since attending [[Lady Gabriella Kingston]]'s wedding in May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50870869|title=Prince Philip taken to hospital as a 'precautionary measure'|work=BBC News|date=20 December 2019|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personality and image==\n[[File:Prins Philip (1982).jpg|thumb|Philip at the World Championship Coach-and-fours, 1982]]\nPhilip played [[polo]] until 1971, when he started to compete in [[Combined driving|carriage driving]], a sport which he helped to expand; the early rule book was drafted under his supervision.<ref>Heald, pp. 212\u2013214</ref> He was also a keen yachtsman and struck up a friendship in 1949 with [[Uffa Fox]], in [[Cowes]]. Philip and the Queen regularly attended [[Cowes Week]] in [[HMY Britannia|HMY ''Britannia'']]. His first airborne flying lesson took place in 1952; by his 70th birthday he had accrued 5,150 pilot hours.<ref>Heald, pp. 148\u2013149</ref> He was presented with [[Royal Air Force]] wings in 1953.<ref>{{cite web|last=Monarchy |first=British |url=https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/ArmedForces/TheRoyalAirForce.aspx |title=The Royal Air Force |website=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=6 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617152205/http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/ArmedForces/TheRoyalAirForce.aspx |archivedate=17 June 2013 }}</ref> In April 2014, it was reported that an old [[British Pathe]] newsreel film had been discovered of Philip's 1962 two-month flying tour of [[South America]]. Filmed sitting alongside Philip at the aircraft's controls was his co-pilot [[Family of Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Captain Peter Middleton]], the grandfather of the Duke's granddaughter-in-law, [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sparkes|first=Matthew|title=Royal couples' grandparents' jet-age meeting|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/10779536/Pictured-Royal-couples-grandparents-jet-age-meeting.html|work=Daily Telegraph|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tominey|first1=Camilla|title=Truth behind Prince George's love of aviation|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/643885/Truth-behind-Prince-George-love-aviation|location=UK |work=Daily Express |date=14 February 2016|accessdate=19 February 2015|quote=It (the photograph) shows the Duchess of Cambridge's grandfather, Captain Peter Middleton, with Prince Philip in 1962...}}</ref>\n[[File:Her Majesty the Queen at Breakfast.jpg|thumb|''Her Majesty the Queen at Breakfast'' painted by her husband in 1957. Biographer [[Robert Lacey]] described the painting as \"a tender portrayal, impressionistic in style, with brushstrokes that are charmingly soft and fuzzy\".<ref>Lacey, p. 368</ref>]]\n\nHe has painted with oils, and collected artworks, including contemporary [[cartoon]]s, which hang at Buckingham Palace, Windsor Castle, Sandringham House, and Balmoral Castle. [[Hugh Casson]] described Philip's own artwork as \"exactly what you'd expect&nbsp;... totally direct, no hanging about. Strong colours, vigorous brushstrokes.\"<ref>Heald, p. 253</ref>\n\nPhilip's down-to-earth manner was attested to by a White House butler who recalled that, on a visit in 1979, Philip had engaged him and a fellow butler in a conversation and poured them drinks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/18/obama-inauguration|location=London |newspaper=The Guardian| first=Christopher|last=Goodwin|title=I'm tickled to death. I never thought I'd see such a thing|date=18 January 2009}}</ref> As well as a reputation for bluntness and plain speaking,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-13682432|title=Prince Philip at 90 on a lifetime of speaking his mind|work=BBC News|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> Philip is noted for occasionally making observations and jokes that have been construed as either funny, or as gaffes: awkward, [[politically incorrect]], or even offensive, but sometimes perceived as stereotypical of someone of his age and background.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/5360412.stm |title=Caught on tape: Infamous gaffes|work=BBC News|date= 19 September 2006|accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,23745347-5007146,00.html |title=Prince Philip right to have a dig at Durie |website=News.com.au |author=Blair, Tim|date=23 May 2008 |accessdate=12 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108233956/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C23599%2C23745347-5007146%2C00.html |archivedate=8 January 2009 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/am/content/2006/s1660067.htm |title=AM&nbsp;\u2013 Prince Philip reminded of blunders on his 85th birthday |work=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20000423/ai_n13948104 |title=The Secret Life of Prince Philip |newspaper=Sunday Herald |date=23 April 2000 |accessdate=12 October 2008 |first=Stephen |last=Naysmith |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206001454/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20000423/ai_n13948104 |archivedate=6 December 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/05/AR2007050500981_pf.html|title=Prince Philip Has a Mouthful Of a Title. And, Often, His Foot|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=12 October 2008|first=Paul|last=Duggan}}</ref> In an address to the General Dental Council in 1960, he jokingly coined a new word for his blunders: \"Dontopedalogy is the science of opening your mouth and putting your foot in it, a science which I have practised for a good many years.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Dolby, Karen |title=The Wicked Wit of Queen Elizabeth II|publisher= Michael O'Mara Books|location= London |date=2015|page= 44}}</ref> Later in life he suggested his comments may have contributed to the perception that he is \"a cantankerous old sod\".<ref>Prince Philip quoted in Brandreth, p. 7</ref>\n\nThe historian [[David Starkey]] described him as a kind of \"HRH [[Victor Meldrew]]\".<ref>Starkey, speaking on BBC News Radio Four, 10 June 2011</ref> For example, in May 1999, British newspapers accused Philip of insulting deaf children at a pop concert in Wales by saying, \"No wonder you are deaf listening to this row.\"<ref>Brandreth, p. 46</ref> Later Philip wrote, \"The story is largely invention. It so happens that my mother was quite seriously deaf and I have been Patron of the Royal National Institute for the Deaf for ages, so it's hardly likely that I would do any such thing.\"<ref>Letter of 4 June 1999 quoted in Brandreth, p. 46</ref> When he and the Queen met Stephen Menary, an army cadet blinded by an IRA bomb, and the Queen enquired how much sight he retained, Philip quipped: \"Not a lot, judging by the tie he's wearing.\" Menary later said: \"I think he just tries to put people at ease by trying to make a joke. I certainly didn't take any offence.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/6805975/Duke-of-Edinburgh-gaffes-by-mocking-blind-boy.html|title=Duke of Edinburgh gaffes by mocking blind boy|last=Leach|first=By Ben|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref>\n\nDuring a state visit to China in 1986, in a private conversation with British students from [[Xi'an]]'s [[Northwest University (China)|North West University]], Philip joked, \"If you stay here much longer, you'll go slit-eyed<!--Prince Philip insists he said \"slit-eyed\" and not \"slitty-eyed\": see Heald, p. 245-->.\"<ref>Heald, pp. 244\u2013245; Lacey, p. 303</ref> The British press reported on the remark as indicative of racial intolerance, but the Chinese authorities were reportedly unconcerned. Chinese students studying in the UK, an official explained, were often told in jest not to stay away too long, lest they go \"round-eyed\".<ref>Lacey, p. 304; see also Heald, p. 245 for a Hong Kong version of the \"round-eyed\" joke.</ref> His comment had no effect on [[China\u2013United Kingdom relations|Sino-British relations]], but it shaped his own reputation.<ref>Heald, p. 246; Lacey, p. 304</ref>\n\n==Portrayals==\nPhilip has been portrayed by several actors including [[Stewart Granger]] (''[[The Royal Romance of Charles and Diana]]'', 1982), [[Christopher Lee]] (''Charles & Diana: A Royal Love Story'', 1982), [[David Threlfall]] (''[[The Queen's Sister]]'', 2005), [[James Cromwell]] (''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'', 2006), and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]], Finn Elliot and [[Tobias Menzies]] (''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'', 2016 onwards).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43581479|title=The Crown: Tobias Menzies cast as new Prince Philip|work=BBC|date=29 March 2018|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrince Philip appears as a fictional character in [[Nevil Shute]]'s novel ''[[In the Wet]]'' (1952), [[Paul Gallico]]'s novel ''Mrs. 'Arris Goes to Moscow'' (1974), [[Tom Clancy]]'s novel ''[[Patriot Games]]'' (1987), and [[Sue Townsend]]'s novel ''[[The Queen and I (novel)|The Queen and I]]'' (1992).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/25/books/the-british-novelist-who-turned-a-class-system-upside-down.html|title=The British Novelist Who Turned A Class System Upside Down|last=Cassidy|first=Suzanne|date=25 December 1993|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-09-16}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nThe prince has authored a number of books:\n* ''Selected Speeches&nbsp;\u2013 1948\u201355'' (1957, revised paperback edition published by [[Nabu Press]] in 2011) {{ISBN|978-1245671330}}\n* ''Selected Speeches&nbsp;\u2013 1956\u201359'' (1960)\n* ''Birds from Britannia'' (1962) (published in the United States as ''Seabirds from Southern Waters'') {{ISBN|978-1163699294}}\n* ''Wildlife Crisis'' with [[James Fisher (naturalist)|James Fisher]] (1970) {{ISBN|978-0402125112}}\n* ''The Environmental Revolution: Speeches on Conservation, 1962\u20131977'' (1978) {{ISBN|978-0846414537}}\n* ''Competition Carriage Driving'' (1982) (published in France 1984, second edition 1984, revised edition 1994) {{ISBN|978-0851315942}}\n* ''A Question of Balance'' (1982) {{ISBN|978-0859550871}}\n* ''Men, Machines and Sacred Cows'' (1984) {{ISBN|978-0241111741}}\n* ''A Windsor Correspondence'' with [[Michael Ashley Mann|Michael Mann]] (1984) {{ISBN|978-0859551083}}\n* ''Down to Earth: Collected Writings and Speeches on Man and the Natural World 1961\u201387'' (1988) (paperback edition 1989, Japanese edition 1992) {{ISBN|978-0828907118}}\n* ''Survival or Extinction: A Christian Attitude to the Environment'' with Michael Mann (1989) {{ISBN|978-0859551588}}\n* ''Driving and Judging Dressage'' (1996) {{ISBN|978-0851316666}}\n* ''30 Years On, and Off, the Box Seat'' (2004) {{ISBN|978-0851318981}}\n\nForewords to:\n*''Royal Australian Navy 1911\u20131961 Jubilee Souvenir'' issued by authority of the Department of the Navy, Canberra (1961)\n* ''The Concise British Flora in Colour'' by [[William Keble Martin]], [[Random House|Ebury Press]]/ [[Michael Joseph (publisher)|Michael Joseph]] (1965)\n* ''Kurt Hahn'' by Hermann R\u00f6hrs and Hilary Tunstall-Behrens (1970)\n* ''The Art of Driving'' by Max Pape (1982) {{ISBN|978-0851313399}}\n*''Yachting and the Royal Prince Alfred Yacht Club'' by Graeme Norman (1988) {{ISBN|978-0867770674}}\n*''[[National Maritime Museum]] Guide to Maritime Britain'' by Keith Wheatley, (2000)\n* ''The Royal Yacht Britannia: The Official History'' by Richard Johnstone-Bryden, [[Conway Publishing|Conway Maritime Press]] (2003) {{ISBN|978-0851779379}}\n* ''1953: The Crowning Year of Sport'' by Jonathan Rice, (2003)\n* ''British Flags and Emblems'' by [[Graham Bartram]], Tuckwell Press (2004) {{ISBN|978-1862322974}}\n* ''Chariots of War'' by Robert Hobson, Ulric Publication (2004) {{ISBN|978-0954199715}}\n* ''RMS Queen Mary 2 Manual: An Insight into the Design, Construction and Operation of the World's Largest Ocean Liner'' by [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]], Haynes Publishing (2014)\n* ''The Triumph of a Great Tradition: The Story of Cunard's 175 Years'' by Eric Flounders and Michael Gallagher, Lily Publications (2014){{ISBN?}}\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n{{Main|List of titles and honours of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n[[File:Prince Philip as Colonel-in-Chief of the Royal Canadian Regiment.jpg|thumb|The Duke of Edinburgh, [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Royal Canadian Regiment]], presenting the 3rd Battalion with their Regimental Colours in April 2013]]\nPhilip has held a number of titles throughout his life. Originally holding the title and style of a [[prince of Greece and Denmark]], Philip abandoned these royal titles prior to his marriage, and was thereafter created a British [[duke]], among other noble titles. The Queen formally issued letters patent in 1957 making Philip a [[British prince]].<ref name=prince />\n\nWhen addressing the Duke of Edinburgh, as with any male member of the royal family except the monarch, the rules of etiquette are to address him the first time as ''Your Royal Highness'', and thereafter as ''Sir''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/etiquette/british-behaviour/r-to-s/royalty.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112125544/http://www.debretts.com/etiquette/british-behaviour/r-to-s/royalty.aspx|archivedate=2010-11-12|title=Royalty \u2013 Debrett's Guide to British Behaviour|date=12 November 2010|publisher=|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Honours and honorary military appointments===\nThe Duke of Edinburgh was appointed by King George VI to the [[Order of the Garter]] on 19 November 1947, the eve of his wedding. Since then, Philip has received 17 different appointments and decorations in the Commonwealth, and 48 from foreign states. The inhabitants of some villages on the island of [[Tanna (island)|Tanna, Vanuatu]] [[Prince Philip Movement|worship Prince Philip as a god]]; the islanders possess portraits of the Duke and hold feasts on his birthday.<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=Nick|title=Is Prince Philip an island god?|publisher=BBC News|date=10 June 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/6734469.stm|accessdate=12 October 2008|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Yaohnanen Tribesmen Show Pictures of 2007 Visit with Prince Philip.jpg|thumb|[[Ni-Vanuatu]] with pictures of Philip]]\nUpon his wife's accession to the throne in 1952, the Duke was appointed Admiral of the [[Sea Cadet Corps (United Kingdom)|Sea Cadet Corps]], [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the British [[Army Cadet Force]], and [[Air Commodore-in-Chief]] of the [[Air Training Corps]].<ref>Heald, p. 111</ref> The following year, he was appointed to the equivalent positions in Canada and made [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]], [[Captain General Royal Marines]], [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]], and [[Marshal of the Royal Air Force]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>Heald, pp. 264\u2013267</ref> Subsequent military appointments were made in [[New Zealand]] and [[Australia]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 407\u2013408; Heald, pp. 264\u2013267</ref> In 1975, he was appointed [[Colonel]] of the [[Grenadier Guards]], a position he handed over to his son Andrew in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/duke-york-appointed-colonel-grenadier-guards|title=The Duke of York is appointed Colonel of the Grenadier Guards|publisher=Royal Household|date=1 December 2017}}</ref> On 16 December 2015, his role as Honorary Air Commodore-in-Chief was handed over to the Duchess of Cambridge.\n\nTo celebrate his 90th birthday, the Queen appointed him [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/duke-edinburgh-appointed-lord-high-admiral|title=The Duke of Edinburgh appointed Lord High Admiral|publisher=royal.uk|date=10 June 2011|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> as well as to the highest ranks available in all three branches of the [[Canadian Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=605239|last=Office of the Prime Minister of Canada|title=PM announces the appointment of His Royal Highness the Duke of Edinburgh to the highest ranks of the Canadian Armed Forces|date=10 June 2011|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=10 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116103058/http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=605239|archive-date=16 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn their 70th wedding anniversary, 20 November 2017, the Queen appointed him Knight Grand Cross (GCVO) of the [[Royal Victorian Order]], making him the first British national since his uncle Earl Mountbatten of Burma to be entitled to wear the breast stars of four orders of chivalry in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Furness|first1=Hannah|title=Queen grants new honour to Prince Philip for 70th wedding anniversary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/20/queen-grants-new-honour-prince-philip-70th-wedding-anniversary/|accessdate=22 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = Coat of Arms of Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.svg\n|bannerimage = Royal Standard of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.svg\n|badgeimage =\n|notes = Following his marriage to Princess Elizabeth until 1949, Prince Philip's arms featured a differenced version of the [[royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom]], derived from his ancestor [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Princess Alice]].<ref name=boutell/><br />Unlike the arms used by other members of the royal family, the Duke's arms no longer features the royal arms of the United Kingdom, as he was granted new arms by King George VI in 1949. However, they do feature elements representing Greece and Denmark, from which he is descended in the male line; the [[Battenberg family|Mountbatten family]] arms, from which he is descended in the female line; and the City of [[Edinburgh]].\n|year_adopted = 19 November 1947\n|escutcheon = '''From 1949:'''<br />[[Quartering (heraldry)|Quarterly]]: First Or, sem\u00e9e of hearts Gules, three lions passant in pale Azure (For [[coat of arms of Denmark|Denmark]]), Second Azure, a cross Argent (For [[national emblem of Greece|Greece]]), Third Argent, two pallets Sable (For Battenberg or Mountbatten), Fourth Argent, upon a rock Proper a castle triple towered Sable, masoned Argent, windows, port, turret-caps and vanes Gules (For [[Coat of arms of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]]), the whole surrounded by the Garter.<ref name=pinches>Pinches, J. H. & R. V., The Royal Heraldry of England, 1974, Heraldry Today.</ref>\n|helm =Upon a coronet of a son of the sovereign Proper, the royal helm Or<ref name=pinches/>\n|crest =Issuant from a ducal coronet Or, a plume of five ostrich feathers alternately Sable and Argent;\n|torse =Mantling Or and ermine\n|supporters = Dexter, a representation of a [[wild man#Heraldry|wild man]] girt about the loins with a lion skin, crowned with a chaplet of oak leaves, holding in the dexter hand a club Proper (from the Danish and Greek royal coat of arms); sinister, a lion queue fourch\u00e9e ducally crowned Or and gorged with a naval coronet Azure;\n|compartment =\n|motto = '''GOD IS MY HELP'''\n|orders = The [[Order of the Garter]] ribbon<br />'''HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE'''<br />''(Shamed be he who thinks evil of it)''\n|other_elements =\n|banner = A banner of the Duke's arms is used as his personal standard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofedinburgh.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113231609/http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofedinburgh.html|archivedate=2009-01-13|title=Duke of Edinburgh|date=13 January 2009|publisher=|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n|badge =\n|symbolism = The arms of Denmark and Greece, represent the Duke of Edinburgh's familial lineage. The arms of the City of Edinburgh represent Philip's dukedom. The naval crown collar alludes to the Duke's naval career.\n|previous_versions = [[File:Arms of Philip Mountbatten (1947-1949).svg|right|100px]]\n'''From 1947 to 1949''':<br />\n\"[[Coat of arms of the Kingdom of Greece|Arms of Greece]] surmounted by an inescutcheon of the arms of Denmark; and over all in the first quarter the arms of [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Princess Alice]], daughter of [[Queen Victoria]], viz, the [[Royal Arms of the United Kingdom|Royal Arms]] differenced with a label of three points argent, the middle point charged with a rose gules and each of the others with an ermine spot. The shield is encircled by the Garter and ensigned with a princely coronet of crosses patt\u00e9e and fleurs-de-lis, above which is placed a barred helm affronte, and thereon the crest; out of a ducal coronet or, a plume of five ostrich feathers alternately sable and argent. The supporters are, dexter, the figure of Hercules proper, and sinister, a lion queue fourche ducally crowned or, gorged with a naval coronet azure.\"<ref name=boutell>Boutell's Heraldry. (1973) {{ISBN|0-7232-1708-4}}.</ref>\n}}\n\n==Issue==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Name\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Birth\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Marriage\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Their children\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Their grandchildren\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Spouse\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 14 November 1948\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 29 July 1981<br /><small>Divorced 28 August 1996</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Lady Diana Spencer]]\n| [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]]\n| [[Prince George of Cambridge]]<br />[[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge]]<br />[[Prince Louis of Cambridge]]\n|-\n| [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]]\n| [[Archie Mountbatten-Windsor]]\n|-\n| 9 April 2005\n| [[Camilla Parker Bowles]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 15 August 1950\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 14 November 1973<br /><small>Divorced 28 April 1992</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Mark Phillips]]\n| [[Peter Phillips]]\n| Savannah Phillips<br />Isla Phillips\n|-\n| [[Zara Tindall]]\n| Mia Tindall<br />Lena Tindall\n|-\n| 12 December 1992\n| [[Timothy Laurence]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" | [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 19 February 1960\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 23 July 1986<br /><small>Divorced 30 May 1996</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Sarah Ferguson]]\n| [[Princess Beatrice of York]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n| [[Princess Eugenie, Mrs Jack Brooksbank]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" | [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 10 March 1964\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 19 June 1999\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Sophie Rhys-Jones]]\n| [[Lady Louise Windsor]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n| [[James, Viscount Severn]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|}\n\n==Ancestry==\nBoth Philip and Queen Elizabeth II are great-great-grandchildren of [[Queen Victoria]], Elizabeth by descent from Victoria's eldest son, [[King Edward VII]], and Philip by descent from Victoria's second daughter, [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Princess Alice]]. Both are also descended from [[King Christian IX of Denmark]].\n\nPhilip is also related to the [[House of Romanov]] through both of his parents. He is a direct descendant of Emperor [[Nicholas I of Russia]] via his paternal grandmother Grand Duchess [[Olga Constantinovna of Russia]].<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Hugh Massingberd|last=Montgomery-Massingberd|first=Hugh (ed.)|year=1977|title=Burke's Royal Families of the World'', 1st edition''|location=London|publisher=Burke's Peerage|isbn=0-85011-023-8|ref=harv|pages=469\u2013474}}</ref> and his maternal grandmother, [[Princess Victoria of Hesse and by Rhine]], was a sister of [[Alexandra Feodorovna (Alix of Hesse)]], wife of [[Nicholas II of Russia|Emperor Nicholas II]].\n\nIn 1993, scientists were able to confirm the identity of the remains of several members of the Romanov family, more than 70 years after their [[execution of the Romanov family|massacre in 1918]], by comparing their [[mitochondrial DNA]] to living [[matrilineal]] relatives, including Philip. Philip, Alexandra, and her children are all descended from [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom]], the daughter of [[Queen Victoria]], through a purely female line.<ref name=gill>{{cite journal |last1=Gill |first1=Peter |last2=Ivanov |first2=Pavel L. |last3=Kimpton |first3=Colin |last4=Piercy |first4=Romelle |last5=Benson |first5=Nicola |last6=Tully |first6=Gillian |last7=Evett |first7=Ian |last8=Hagelberg |first8=Erika|authorlink8=Erika Hagelberg |last9=Sullivan |first9=Kevin |date=February 1994 |title=Identification of the remains of the Romanov family by DNA analysis |journal=Nature Genetics |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=130\u2013135 |doi=10.1038/ng0294-130 |pmid=8162066 }}</ref>\n\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes|align=center\n|ref=<ref>{{cite book |last=Louda |first=Ji\u0159\u00ed |last2=Maclagan |first2=Michael |authorlink2=Michael Maclagan |year=1999 |origyear=1981 |title=Lines of Succession: Heraldry of the Royal Families of Europe |edition=2nd |location=London |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=978-0-316-84820-6 |page=34 }}</ref><!--source for all 15-->\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]]\n|4= 4. [[George I of Greece]]\n|5= 5. [[Grand Duchess Olga Constantinovna of Russia]]\n|6= 6. [[Prince Louis of Battenberg]]\n|7= 7. [[Princess Victoria of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|8= 8. [[Christian IX of Denmark]]\n|9= 9. [[Louise of Hesse-Kassel|Princess Louise of Hesse-Kassel]]\n|10= 10. [[Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolayevich of Russia]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Alexandra of Saxe-Altenburg]]\n|12= 12. [[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|13= 13. [[Julia, Princess of Battenberg|Countess Julia von Hauke]]\n|14= 14. [[Louis IV, Grand Duke of Hesse|Louis IV, Grand Duke of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|15= 15. [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=fn}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Alexandra of Yugoslavia]] (1959). ''Prince Philip: A Family Portrait''. London: Hodder and Stoughton.\n* [[Basil Boothroyd|Boothroyd, Basil]] (1971). ''Prince Philip: An Informal Biography''. New York: McCall. {{ISBN|0-841-50116-5}}\n* [[Gyles Brandreth|Brandreth, Gyles]] (2004). ''Philip and Elizabeth: Portrait of a Marriage''. London: Century. {{ISBN|0-7126-6103-4}}\n* Eade, Philip (2011). ''Prince Philip: The Turbulent Early Life of the Man Who Married Queen Elizabeth II''. New York: St. Martin's Griffin. {{ISBN|978-1-250-01363-7}}\n* [[Tim Heald|Heald, Tim]] (1991). ''The Duke: A Portrait of Prince Philip''. London: Hodder and Stoughton. {{ISBN|0-340-54607-7}}\n* [[Robert Lacey|Lacey, Robert]] (2002). ''Royal: Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II''. London: Little, Brown. {{ISBN|0-316-85940-0}}\n* [[Hugo Vickers|Vickers, Hugo]] (2000). ''Alice, Princess Andrew of Greece''. London: Hamish Hamilton. {{ISBN|0-241-13686-5}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q80976|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no|c=category:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n* [https://www.royal.uk/the-duke-of-edinburgh The Duke of Edinburgh at the Royal Family website]\n* {{Britannica|456258|Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/timelines/zqqy2nb Duke of Edinburgh's profile] on [[BBC]]\n* [http://www.dofe.org/ The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]\n* {{IMDb name|0697611|Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111206103156/http://www.life.com/gallery/58221/in-the-words-of-prince-philip#index/0 In the Words of Prince Philip]&nbsp;\u2013 slideshow by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]''\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/013568}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg]]|10 June|1921}}\n{{S-roy|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon]]|as=[[queen consort]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of British consorts|Consort of the British monarch]]\n|years=6 February 1952&nbsp;\u2013 present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-new|creation}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Duke of Edinburgh]]|years=1947\u2013present}}\n{{S-inc|heir=[[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]]}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-aca}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Victor Hope, 2nd Marquess of Linlithgow|The Marquess of<br />Linlithgow]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Chancellor of the University of Edinburgh]]|years=1953\u20132010}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]]}}\n{{S-new|institution}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[University of Salford|Chancellor of the University of Salford]]|years=1967\u20131991}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Sarah, Duchess of York|The Duchess of York]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edgar Adrian, 1st Baron Adrian|The Lord Adrian]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Chancellor of the University of Cambridge]]|years=1976\u20132011}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Turville|The Lord Sainsbury of Turville]]}}\n{{S-hon}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Grand Masters of the Order of the British Empire|Grand Master of the Order of the British Empire]]\n|years=24 March 1953&nbsp;\u2013 present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[King George VI]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Air Commodore-in-Chief]] of the [[Air Training Corps]]|years=1953\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|The Duchess of Cambridge]]<br /><small>As [[Air Commodore|Air Commandant]]</small>}}\n{{S-mil}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Queen Elizabeth II]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]]\n|years=10 June 2011&nbsp;\u2013 present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[India Hicks]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Line of succession to the British throne]]|creation=(descended from [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Alice]], daughter of [[Queen Victoria]])}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Maximilian, Margrave of Baden|The Margrave of Baden]]}}\n{{S-prec}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Elizabeth II|The Sovereign]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom]]}}\n{{S-fol|after=[[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales,<br />Duke of Rothesay]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Gentlemen)|Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, Prince}}\n{{British consort}}\n{{Current consorts of sovereigns}}\n{{British princes}}\n{{Chancellors of the University of Cambridge}}\n{{Greek princes}}\n{{Danish princes}}\n{{Battenberg family}}\n{{Current British dukes}}\n{{Members of the Order of the Garter}}\n{{Dukes of Edinburgh|Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, Prince}}\n{{The Football Association}}\n{{Order of New Zealand}}\n{{FRS 1951}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philip Of Edinburgh, Duke, Prince}}\n[[Category:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh| ]]\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British people]]\n[[Category:People from Corfu]]\n[[Category:British people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of German descent]]\n[[Category:British people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Greek emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n<!-- Monarchy/nobility -->\n[[Category:British royal consorts]]\n[[Category:Danish princes]]\n[[Category:Greek princes]]\n[[Category:Princes of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor]]\n[[Category:Battenberg family]]\n[[Category:House of Gl\u00fccksburg (Greece)]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Australia]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Canada]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Deified people]]\n\n<!-- WARNING : Orders and decorations : moved to [[List of titles and honours of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]] -->\n\n<!-- Military -->\n[[Category:Lords of the Admiralty]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals of the fleet]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines generals]]\n[[Category:British field marshals]]\n[[Category:Marshals of the Royal Air Force]]\n[[Category:Field marshals of Australia]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force air marshals]]\n<!-- Privy Council, Learned Societies and Academia -->\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society (Statute 12)]]\n[[Category:Honorary fellows of the Royal Microscopical Society]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Smeatonian Society of Civil Engineers]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People educated at Cheam School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gordonstoun]]\n<!-- Religion -->\n[[Category:British Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Vanuatu deities]]\n<!-- Miscellaneous -->\n[[Category:British environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Chartered designers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Football Association]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Marylebone Cricket Club]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Zoological Society of London]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:Members of Trinity House]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of Water Rats members|*]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Schule Schloss Salem]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Prince Philip}}\n{{short description|Member of the British Royal Family, consort to Queen Elizabeth II}}\n{{Infobox royalty \n| consort       = yes\n| name          = Prince Philip\n| title         = [[Duke of Edinburgh]] ([[List of titles and honours of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|more]])\n| image         = 25.Jun.2015 Prince Philip in Frankfurt.jpg\n| caption       = Prince Philip in June 2015\n| succession    = [[List of British royal consorts|Consort of the British monarch]]\n| reign         = 6 February 1952&nbsp;\u2013 present\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Queen Elizabeth II]]|20 November 1947}}\n| issue-link    = #Issue\n| issue         = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n* [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\n* [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]]}}\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| house          = {{plainlist|\n*[[House of Gl\u00fccksburg|Gl\u00fccksburg]] (until 1947)\n*[[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]] (from 1947)\n*[[House of Windsor|Windsor]] (from 1947){{citation-needed|reason=\"husband doesn't belongs to wifes house on marriage by default\"|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n| father         = [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]]\n| mother         = [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]] \n| birth_name     = Prince Philip of Greece and Denmark\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1921|06|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mon Repos, Corfu|Mon Repos]], [[Corfu]],<br> [[Kingdom of Greece]]\n| signature      = Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh signature.png\n| module         = {{Infobox military person | embed=yes\n | allegiance    = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n | branch        = {{navy|United Kingdom}}<br />{{army|United Kingdom}}<br />{{air force|United Kingdom}}\n | serviceyears  = 1939\u20131952 <br />(active service)\n | rank          = [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]<br />[[Field Marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]]<br />[[Marshal of the Royal Air Force]]\n | servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records -->\n | unit          = \n | commands      = [[HMS Magpie (U82)|HMS ''Magpie'']]\n | battles_label = \n | battles       = [[Second World War]]\n*[[Battle of Crete]]\n*[[Battle of Cape Matapan]]\n*[[Allied invasion of Sicily]]\n*[[Operation Dragoon]]\n*[[Operation Robson]]\n*[[Operation Lentil (Sumatra)|Operation Lentil]]\n*[[Battle of Okinawa]]\n | awards        = {{plain list|\n* [[Mentioned in dispatches]]\n* [[Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] with Palm\n* [[Greek War Cross]]}}\n  }}\n}}\n{{British Royal Family}}\n\n'''Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh''' (born '''Prince Philip of Greece and Denmark''',<ref>[http://www.canadianheritage.gc.ca/eng/1287056173925/1297368439340 Canadian Heritage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317231641/http://www.canadianheritage.gc.ca/eng/1287056173925/1297368439340 |date=17 March 2012 }}; [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-philip/8566735/Prince-Philips-90th-birthday-a-life-less-ordinary-for-The-Duke-of-Edinburgh.html Daily Telegraph]; [http://news.sky.com/story/861428/the-life-and-times-of-the-royal-consort Sky News]; [https://www.royal.uk/the-duke-of-edinburgh Website of the Royal Family], all retrieved 10 June 2011</ref> 10 June 1921),{{#tag:ref|He was born on 10&nbsp;June 1921 according to the [[Gregorian calendar]]. Until 1&nbsp;March 1923, Greece used the [[Julian calendar]], in which the date is 28&nbsp;May 1921.|group=fn}} is the husband of [[Queen Elizabeth II]] of the [[United Kingdom]] and other [[Commonwealth realm]]s.\n\nPhilip was born into the [[Greek royal family|Greek]] and [[Danish royal family|Danish royal families]]. He was born in [[Greece]], but his family was exiled from the country when he was an infant. After being educated in France, Germany, and the United Kingdom, he joined the British [[Royal Navy]] in 1939, aged 18. From July 1939, he began corresponding with the 13-year-old Princess Elizabeth, whom he had first met in 1934. During the [[Second World War]] he served with distinction in the [[Mediterranean Fleet|Mediterranean]] and [[British Pacific Fleet|Pacific]] Fleets. After the war, Philip was granted permission by [[George VI]] to marry Elizabeth. Before the official announcement of their engagement in July 1947, he abandoned his Greek and Danish royal titles, became a naturalised [[British subject]], and adopted his maternal grandparents' surname [[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]]. He [[Wedding of Princess Elizabeth and Philip Mountbatten|married Elizabeth]] on 20 November 1947. Just before the wedding, he was created [[Duke of Edinburgh]], [[Earl of Merioneth]] and [[Baron Greenwich]]. Philip left active military service when Elizabeth became queen in 1952, having reached the rank of [[Commander (Royal Navy)|commander]], and was formally made a [[British prince]] in 1957.\n\nPhilip and Elizabeth have four children: [[Prince Charles]], [[Princess Anne]], [[Prince Andrew]], and [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]]. Through a British [[Order in Council]] issued in 1960, descendants of the couple not bearing royal styles and titles can use the surname [[Mountbatten-Windsor]], which has also been used by some members of the royal family who do hold titles, such as Princess Anne, and Princes Andrew and Edward.\n\nA keen sports enthusiast, Philip helped develop the equestrian event of [[carriage driving]]. He is a patron, president, or member of over 780 organisations, and he serves as chairman of [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] for people aged 14 to 24.<ref>{{cite web |title=Do your DofE \u2013 The Duke of Edinburgh's Award |url=https://www.dofe.org/do-your-dofe/ |website=dofe.org |accessdate=29 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129181534/https://www.dofe.org/do-your-dofe/ |archive-date=29 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is the longest-serving consort of a reigning British monarch and the oldest ever male member of the [[British royal family]]. Philip retired from his royal duties on 2 August 2017, aged 96, having completed 22,219 solo engagements since 1952.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Corfu Mon Repos R01.jpg|left|thumb|[[Mon Repos, Corfu|Mon Repos]], Philip's birthplace]]\nPrince Philip of Greece and Denmark was born in [[Mon Repos, Corfu|Mon Repos]] on the Greek island of [[Corfu]] on 10 June 1921, the only son and fifth and final child of [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]] and [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]].<ref>Brandreth, p. 56</ref> A member of the [[House of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg]], itself a branch of the [[House of Oldenburg]], he was a prince of both [[Greece]] and [[Denmark]] by virtue of his patrilineal descent from [[George I of Greece]] and [[Christian IX of Denmark]], and he was from birth in the line of succession to both thrones; the 1953 [[Act of Succession (Denmark)|Succession Act]] removed his family branch's succession rights in Denmark.<ref>{{cite book |last=T\u00e5gholt |first=Knud |year=1963 |title=Det gl\u00fccksburgske kongehus, fra Christian IX til prinsesse Margrethe:\u00a0Den danske kongesl\u00e6gt gennem hundrede \u00e5r, 1863\u20131963 |url= |location= |publisher=Aros |page=6 |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> Philip's four elder sisters were [[Princess Margarita of Greece and Denmark|Margarita]], [[Princess Theodora of Greece and Denmark (1906\u20131969)|Theodora]], [[Princess Cecilie of Greece and Denmark|Cecilie]], and [[Princess Sophie of Greece and Denmark|Sophie]]. He was baptised in the [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] rite at [[Old Fortress, Corfu|St. George's Church in the Old Fortress]] in Corfu.\n\nShortly after Philip's birth, his maternal grandfather, [[Prince Louis of Battenberg]], then known as Louis Mountbatten, [[Marquess of Milford Haven]], died in London. Louis was a naturalised British citizen, who, after a career in the [[Royal Navy]], had renounced his German titles and adopted the surname [[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]]\u2014an Anglicised version of [[Battenberg family|Battenberg]]\u2014during the [[World War I|First World War]], owing to [[Anti-German sentiment#First World War|anti-German sentiment]] in the United Kingdom. After visiting London for the memorial, Philip and his mother returned to Greece where Prince Andrew had remained behind to command an army division embroiled in the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u20131922)]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 58\u201359</ref>\n\nThe war went badly for Greece, and the Turks made large gains. On 22 September 1922, Philip's uncle, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine I]], was forced to abdicate and the new military government arrested Prince Andrew, along with others. The commander of the army, General [[Georgios Hatzianestis]], and five senior [[Trial of the Six|politicians were executed]]. Prince Andrew's life was believed to be in danger, and Alice was under surveillance. In December, a revolutionary court banished Prince Andrew from Greece for life.<ref>{{cite journal|title=News in Brief: Prince Andrew's Departure|journal=The Times|date=5 December 1922|page=12}}</ref> The British naval vessel [[HMS Calypso (D61)|HMS ''Calypso'']] evacuated Prince Andrew's family, with Philip carried to safety in a cot made from a fruit box. Philip's family went to France, where they settled in the Paris suburb of [[Saint-Cloud]] in a house lent to them by his wealthy aunt, [[Princess George of Greece and Denmark]].<ref>Alexandra, pp. 35\u201337; Heald, p. 31; Vickers, pp. 176\u2013178</ref>\n\nBecause Philip left Greece as a baby, he does not speak [[Greek language|Greek]]. In 1992, he said that he \"could understand a certain amount\".<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/a-strange-life-profile-of-prince-philip-1563268.html |work=The Independent |location=London |title=A strange life: Profile of Prince Philip |first=Fiammetta |last=Rocco |date=13 December 1992 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Philip has stated that he thought of himself as Danish, and his family spoke English, French, and German.<ref name=independent /> Philip, who in his youth was known for his charm, was linked to a number of women, including [[Osla Benning]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/romances-young-prince-philip/ |title=The romances of young Prince Philip |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Philip |last=Eade |date=5 May 2017 |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Youth==\n===Education===\n\n[[File:G House from the South Lawn on an Autumn Afternoon.jpg|thumb|Philip studied at [[Gordonstoun]] School, Scotland.]]\n\nPhilip was first educated at The Elms,<ref name=\"basil\">{{cite book |last1=Boothroyd |first1=Basil |title=Prince Philip: An Informal Biography |date=1971 |publisher=McCall Publishing Company |location=New York |isbn=0841501165 |edition=First American}}</ref> an American school in Paris run by Donald MacJannet, who described Philip as a \"know it all smarty person, but always remarkably polite\".<ref>Alexandra, p. 42; Heald, p. 34. Fellow pupils at the school included [[Queen Anne of Romania|Princess Anne of Bourbon-Parma]], who later married King [[Michael of Romania]].</ref> In 1928, he was sent to the United Kingdom to attend [[Cheam School]], living with his maternal grandmother, [[Victoria Mountbatten, Dowager Marchioness of Milford Haven]], at [[Kensington Palace]] and his uncle, [[George Mountbatten, 2nd Marquess of Milford Haven]], at Lynden Manor in [[Bray, Berkshire]].<ref>Heald, pp. 35\u201339</ref> In the next three years, his four sisters married German princes and moved to Germany, his mother was diagnosed with [[schizophrenia]] and placed in an asylum,<ref>Brandreth, p. 66; Vickers, p. 205</ref> and his father took up residence in [[Monte Carlo]].<ref>Eade, p. 104</ref> Philip had little contact with his mother for the remainder of his childhood.<ref>Brandreth, p. 67</ref> In 1933, he was sent to [[Schule Schloss Salem]] in Germany, which had the \"advantage of saving school fees\" because it was owned by the family of his brother-in-law, [[Berthold, Margrave of Baden]].<ref>Prince Philip quoted in Brandreth, p. 72</ref> With the rise of [[Nazism]] in Germany, Salem's Jewish founder, [[Kurt Hahn]], fled persecution and founded [[Gordonstoun]] School in Scotland, to which Philip moved after two terms at Salem.<ref>Brandreth, p. 72; Heald, p. 42</ref> In 1937, his sister [[Princess Cecilie of Greece and Denmark|Cecilie]], her husband [[Georg Donatus, Hereditary Grand Duke of Hesse]], her two young sons, [[Prince Ludwig of Hesse and by Rhine|Ludwig]] and [[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine (1933\u20131937)|Alexander]], her newborn infant, and her mother-in-law, [[Princess Eleonore of Solms-Hohensolms-Lich]], were killed in [[Sabena OO-AUB Ostend crash|an air crash at Ostend]]; Philip, then 16 years old, attended the funeral in [[Darmstadt]].<ref>Brandreth, p. 69; Vickers, p. 273</ref><!--also in Heald--> The following year, his uncle and guardian Lord Milford Haven died of [[bone marrow cancer]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 77, 136<!--Heald says cancer but does not specify--></ref>\n\n===Naval and wartime service===\n[[File:HMS Valiant-2.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Philip served aboard {{HMS|Valiant|1914|6}} in the [[Battle of the Mediterranean]]]]\nAfter leaving Gordonstoun in early 1939, Philip completed a term as a cadet at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], then repatriated to Greece, living with his mother in Athens for a month in mid-1939. At the behest of the Greek king, [[George II of Greece|George II]], he returned to Britain in September to resume training for the [[Royal Navy]].<ref>Eade, pp. 129\u2013130; Vickers, pp. 284\u2013285, 433.</ref> He graduated from Dartmouth the next year as the best cadet in his course.<ref name=royalgov>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Navalcareer.aspx |title=Naval career |publisher=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=7 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529132154/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Navalcareer.aspx |archivedate=29 May 2010}}</ref> During the Second World War, he continued to serve in the British forces, while two of his brothers-in-law, [[Prince Christoph of Hesse]] and [[Berthold, Margrave of Baden]], fought on the opposing German side.<ref>Vickers, pp. 293\u2013295.</ref> Philip was appointed as a midshipman in January 1940. He spent four months on the battleship {{HMS|Ramillies|07|6}}, protecting convoys of the [[Second Australian Imperial Force|Australian Expeditionary Force]] in the Indian Ocean, followed by shorter postings on {{HMS|Kent|54|6}}, on {{HMS|Shropshire|73|6}}, and in [[Ceylon]].<ref>Eade, pp. 132\u2013133.</ref> After the [[Greco-Italian War|invasion of Greece by Italy]] in October 1940, he was transferred from the Indian Ocean to the battleship {{HMS|Valiant|1914|6}} in the [[Mediterranean Fleet (United Kingdom)|Mediterranean Fleet]].<ref>Heald, p. 60.</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 1941,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35455|date=13 February 1942 |page=715 |supp= |nolink=y}}</ref> Philip was commissioned as a sub-lieutenant after a series of courses at [[Portsmouth]], in which he gained the top grade in four out of five sections of the qualifying examination.<ref>Brandreth, p. 154; Heald, p. 66.</ref> Among other engagements, he was involved in the [[battle of Crete]], and was [[mentioned in dispatches]] for his service during the [[battle of Cape Matapan]],<ref name=\"basil\" /> in which he controlled the battleship's searchlights. He was also awarded the [[Greek War Cross]] of Valour.<ref name=royalgov /> In June 1942, he was appointed to the [[V and W-class destroyer]] and flotilla leader [[Thornycroft type leader|HMS ''Wallace'']], which was involved in convoy escort tasks on the east coast of Britain, as well as the [[Allied invasion of Sicily]].<ref name=\"smith\">{{cite web| last=Smith| first=David| title=Prince Philip's war heroics come to light after 60 years| newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 December 2003| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/28/monarchy.davidsmith| accessdate=12 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nPromotion to lieutenant followed on 16 July 1942.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35664|date=11 August 1942 |page=3510 |supp=|nolink=y}}</ref> In October of the same year, he became first lieutenant of HMS ''Wallace'', at 21 years old one of the youngest first lieutenants in the Royal Navy. During the invasion of Sicily, in July 1943, as second in command of ''Wallace'', he saved his ship from a night bomber attack. He devised a plan to launch a raft with smoke floats that successfully distracted the bombers, allowing the ship to slip away unnoticed.<ref name=\"smith\"/> In 1944, he moved on to the new destroyer, {{HMS|Whelp|R37|6}}, where he saw service with the [[British Pacific Fleet]] in the 27th Destroyer Flotilla.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 155\u2013163; Heald, pp. 66\u201367.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/xGM-Chrono-10DD-63W-Whelp.htm |title=HMS Whelp, destroyer |publisher=Naval-history.net |accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> He was present in [[Tokyo Bay]] when the instrument of [[Japanese surrender]] was signed. Philip returned to the United Kingdom on the ''Whelp'' in January 1946, and was posted as an instructor at {{HMS|Royal Arthur|shore establishment|6}}, the Petty Officers' School in [[Corsham]], Wiltshire.<ref>Brandreth, p. 176.</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\n{{further|Wedding of Princess Elizabeth and Philip Mountbatten}}\n[[File:Royal Monogram of Prince Philip of Great Britain.svg|thumb|upright|Philip's monogram]]\nIn 1939, [[King George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] toured the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]]. During the visit, the Queen and [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]] asked Philip to escort the King's two daughters, [[Elizabeth II|Elizabeth]] and [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Margaret]], who were Philip's [[Royal descendants of Queen Victoria and King Christian IX#Monarchs descended from Queen Victoria|third cousins]] through [[Queen Victoria]], and [[Royal descendants of Queen Victoria and King Christian IX#Monarchs descended from King Christian IX|second cousins once removed]] through [[King Christian IX of Denmark]].<ref>[[Alexandra of Yugoslavia|Queen Alexandra of Yugoslavia]] quoted in Heald, p. 57</ref> Elizabeth fell in love with Philip, and they began to exchange letters when she was 13.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 132\u2013136, 166\u2013168</ref>\n\nEventually, in the summer of 1946, Philip asked the King for his daughter's hand in marriage. The King granted his request, provided that any formal engagement be delayed until Elizabeth's 21st birthday the following April.<ref>Brandreth, p. 183</ref> By March 1947, Philip had abandoned his Greek and Danish royal titles, had adopted the surname [[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]] from his mother's family, and had become a naturalised British subject. The engagement was announced to the public on 10 July 1947.<ref>Heald, p. 77</ref>\n\nThough Philip appeared \"always to have regarded himself as an Anglican\",<ref>''The Times'', 10 July 1947, p. 4</ref> and he had attended Anglican services with his classmates and relations in England and throughout his Royal Navy days, he had been baptised in the Greek Orthodox Church. The [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Geoffrey Fisher]], wanted to \"regularise\" Philip's position by officially receiving him into the Church of England,<ref>{{cite book |author=Boothroyd, Basil |authorlink=Basil Boothroyd |year=1971 |title=Prince Philip: An Informal Biography |publisher=McCall |isbn=0841501165 |pages=45\u201347}}</ref> which he did in October 1947.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1947/10/04/archives/elizabeths-fiance-now-an-anglican.html \"Elizabeth's Fiance Now an Anglican\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'', 4 October 1947</ref>\n\nThe day before the wedding, King George VI bestowed the [[Style (manner of address)|style]] of ''[[Royal Highness]]'' on Philip and, on the morning of the wedding, 20 November 1947, he was made the [[Duke of Edinburgh]], [[Earl of Merioneth]], and [[Baron Greenwich]] of Greenwich in the County of London.<ref name=\"LG 21 Nov 1947\">{{London Gazette |issue=38128 |pages=5495\u20135496 |date=21 November 1947}}</ref> Consequently, being already a [[Knight of the Garter]], between 19 and 20 November 1947 he bore the unusual style His Royal Highness Sir Philip Mountbatten, and is so described in the [[Letters Patent]] of 20 November 1947.<ref name=\"LG 21 Nov 1947\"/>\n\nPhilip and Elizabeth were married in a ceremony at [[Westminster Abbey]], recorded and broadcast by [[BBC]] radio to 200&nbsp;million people around the world.<ref>Heald, p. 86</ref> In post-war Britain it was not acceptable for any of the Duke of Edinburgh's German relations to be invited to the wedding, including Philip's three surviving sisters, all of whom had married German princes. After their marriage, the Duke and Duchess of Edinburgh took up residence at [[Clarence House]]. Their first two children were born before Elizabeth succeeded her father as monarch in 1952:  [[Prince Charles]] in 1948 and [[Princess Anne]] in 1950. Their marriage is now the longest of any British monarch.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7101094.stm |title=Queen celebrates diamond wedding |date=19 November 2007 |accessdate=10 February 2017 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/9689130/Queen-and-Duke-of-Edinburgh-celebrate-65th-wedding-anniversary.html |title=Queen and Duke of Edinburgh celebrate 65th wedding anniversary |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=19 November 2012 |accessdate=10 February 2017 |first=Gordon |last=Rayner}}</ref>\n\nPhilip was introduced to the [[House of Lords]] on 21 July 1948,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh |title=HRH The Duke of Edinburgh (Lords Sitting of 21 July 1948) |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820064849/https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh |archive-date=20 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> immediately before his uncle Louis Mountbatten, who had been made [[Earl Mountbatten of Burma]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/earl-mountbatten-of-burma |title=Earl Mountbatten of Burma (Lords Sitting of 21 July 1948) |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820064857/https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1948/jul/21/earl-mountbatten-of-burma |archive-date=20 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Philip, like his sons Charles and Andrew and other royals (with the exception of the [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|1st Earl of Snowdon]]), ceased to be members of the House of Lords following the [[House of Lords Act 1999]]. He never spoke in the House.\n\n[[File:Princess Elizabeth, Prince Philip and Louis St. Laurent.jpg|thumb|1951 tour of Canada with Prime Minister [[Louis St. Laurent]]]]\nAfter his honeymoon at the Mountbatten family home, [[Broadlands]], Philip returned to the navy at first in a desk job at [[the Admiralty]], and later on a staff course at the [[Royal Naval College (Greenwich)|Naval Staff College, Greenwich]].<ref>Alexandra, pp. 100, 105\u2013106</ref> From 1949, he was stationed in [[Malta]] (residing at [[Villa Guardamangia]]) after being posted as the first lieutenant of the destroyer [[HMS Chequers (R61)|HMS ''Chequers'']], the lead ship of the 1st Destroyer Flotilla in the Mediterranean Fleet.<ref>Heald, p. 94</ref> On 16 July 1950, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant commander (Royal Navy)|lieutenant commander]] and given command of the frigate [[HMS Magpie (U82)|HMS ''Magpie'']].<ref>Heald, p. 95</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38994 |supp=y |page=4152 |date=15 August 1950}}</ref> On 30 June 1952, Philip was promoted to [[Commander (Royal Navy)|commander]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39597 |supp= |page=3821 |date=15 July 1952}}</ref> though his active naval career had ended in July 1951.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Militaryinvolvement.aspx |title=The Duke of Edinburgh > Military involvement |publisher=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=7 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528151405/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Militaryinvolvement.aspx |archivedate=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Heald, p. 97</ref>\n\nWith the King in ill health, Princess Elizabeth and the Duke of Edinburgh were both appointed to the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] on 4 November 1951, after a coast-to-coast tour of [[Canada]]. At the end of January 1952, Philip and his wife set out on a tour of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]]. On 6 February 1952, they were in [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]] when Elizabeth's father died and she became queen. It was Philip who broke the news to Elizabeth at [[Sagana Lodge]], and the royal party immediately returned to the United Kingdom.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 245\u2013247</ref>\n\n==Consort of the Queen==\n===Royal house===\n\n[[File:Elizabeth and Philip 1953.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Coronation of Elizabeth II|Coronation]] portrait of Elizabeth II with the Duke of Edinburgh, June 1953]]\nThe accession of Elizabeth to the throne brought up the question of the name of the [[royal house]], as Elizabeth would typically have taken Philip's last name upon marriage. The Duke's uncle, Earl Mountbatten of Burma, advocated the name ''House of Mountbatten''. Philip suggested ''House of Edinburgh'', after his ducal title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/9305749/Emma-Soames-As-Churchills-were-proud-to-do-our-duty.html|title=Emma Soames: As Churchills we're proud to do our duty|last=Soames|first=Emma|date=2012-06-01|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> When [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]], Elizabeth's grandmother, heard of this, she informed the British prime minister, [[Winston Churchill]], who himself later advised the Queen to issue a royal proclamation declaring that the royal house was to remain known as the [[House of Windsor]]. Prince Philip privately complained, \"I am nothing but a bloody amoeba. I am the only man in the country not allowed to give his name to his own children.\"<ref>Brandreth, pp. 253\u2013254</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 1960, several years after the death of Queen Mary and the resignation of Churchill as prime minister, the Queen issued an [[Order in Council]] declaring that [[Mountbatten-Windsor]] would be the surname of her and her husband's male-line descendants who are not styled as Royal Highness or titled as prince or princess.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41948/supplement/1003 |work=[[The London Gazette]] |title=Supplement to The London Gazette of Friday, 5th February 1960 |date=8 February 1960}}</ref> While it seems the Queen had \"absolutely set her heart\" on such a change and had it in mind for some time, it occurred only 11 days before the birth of [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Prince Andrew]] (19 February), and only after three months of protracted correspondence between constitutional expert [[Edward Iwi]] (who averred that, without such a change, the royal child would be born with \"the Badge of Bastardy\") and Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]] who had attempted to rebuff Iwi.<ref>Travis, Alan (18 February 1999). [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/feb/18/monarchy \"Queen feared 'slur' on family\", ''The Guardian'']. Retrieved 17 April 2014</ref>\n\nAfter her accession to the throne, the Queen also announced that the Duke was to have \"place, pre-eminence and precedence\" next to her \"on all occasions and in all meetings, except where otherwise provided by [[Act of Parliament]]\". This meant the Duke took precedence over his son, the [[Prince of Wales]], except, officially, in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British parliament]]. In fact, however, he attends Parliament only when escorting the Queen for the annual [[State Opening of Parliament]], where he walks and sits beside her.<ref>British-Japanese Parliamentary Group. [https://web.archive.org/web/20130603102831/http://www.bjpg.co.uk/publications/Tour_of_Parliament_(English).pdf Tour of the Palace of Westminster]. Retrieved 2012/5/2.</ref> Contrary to rumours over the years, the Queen and Duke are said by insiders to have had a strong relationship throughout their marriage, despite the challenges of Elizabeth's reign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Love and Majesty |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/society/2012/01/queen-elizabeth-201201 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"itv\"/> The Queen referred to Prince Philip in a speech on the occasion of her Diamond Jubilee in 2012 as her \"constant strength and guide\".<ref name=\"itv\">{{cite news |title=Prince Philip: The Man At The Queen's Side |date=5 June 2012 |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2012-06-05/prince-philip-the-man-at-the-queens-side/ |publisher=ITV}}</ref>\n\nPrince Philip receives a Parliamentary annuity (of \u00a3359,000 since 1990{{#tag:ref|The amount was set by the Civil List (Increase of Financial Provision) Order 1990. It was initially set at \u00a340,000 in the Civil List Act 1952, raised to \u00a365,000 by the Civil List Act 1972, and raised to \u00a3165,000 by the Civil List (Increase of Financial Provision) Order 1984.|group=fn}}) that serves to meet official expenses in carrying out public duties. The annuity is unaffected by the reform of royal finances under the [[Sovereign Grant Act 2011]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Royal Public Finances |url=https://www.royal.gov.uk/pdf/Introduction%20to%20Head%20of%20State%20expenditure%202006-07.pdf |accessdate=7 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224234303/https://www.royal.gov.uk/pdf/Introduction%20to%20Head%20of%20State%20expenditure%202006-07.pdf |archivedate=24 February 2014}}</ref><ref>\"Living off the State, A critical guide to UK Royal Finance\", Jon Temple, 2nd edition 2012</ref> Any part of the allowance that is not used to meet official expenditure is liable for tax. In practice, the entire allowance is used to fund his official duties.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sovereign grant Act 2011: Tax |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sovereign-grant-act-2011-guidance/sovereign-grant-act-2011-guidance#tax |accessdate=7 August 2014 |publisher=www.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Duties and milestones===\n[[File:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, Cambridge, Waikato (January 1 1954) (17843185594).jpg|thumb|upright|In [[Cambridge, New Zealand]] 1954]]\n\nAs consort to the Queen, Philip supported his wife in her new duties as sovereign, accompanying her to ceremonies such as the [[State Opening of Parliament]] in various countries, state dinners, and tours abroad. As chairman of the [[Coronation of the British monarch|Coronation]] Commission, he was the first member of the royal family to fly in a helicopter, visiting the troops that were to take part in the ceremony.<ref>Brandreth, p. 259</ref> Philip was not crowned in the service, but knelt before Elizabeth, with her hands enclosing his, and swore to be her \"liege man of life and limb\".<ref>Brandreth, p. 263</ref>\n[[File:Prince Philip and Elizabeth II, 1954.jpg|left|thumb|In [[Queensland]], Australia, 1954]]\nIn the early 1950s, his sister-in-law, [[Princess Margaret]], considered marrying a divorced older man, [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]]. The press accused Philip of being hostile to the match, to which he replied \"I haven't done anything.\" Philip had not interfered, preferring to stay out of other people's love lives.<ref>Brandreth, p. 270</ref> Eventually, Margaret and Townsend parted. For six months, over 1953\u201354, Philip and Elizabeth toured the Commonwealth; as with previous tours the children were left in Britain.<ref>Brandreth, p. 278</ref>\n\nIn 1956, the Duke, with [[Kurt Hahn]], founded [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] in order to give young people \"a sense of responsibility to themselves and their communities\". In the same year, he also established the [[Commonwealth Study Conference]]s. From 1956 to 1957, Philip travelled around the world aboard the newly commissioned [[HMY Britannia|HMY ''Britannia'']], during which he opened the [[1956 Summer Olympics]] in Melbourne and visited the [[Antarctica|Antarctic]], becoming the first royal to cross the [[Antarctic Circle]].<ref name=\"royanikkhah\">{{cite web|last1=Nikkhah|first1=Roya|title=Prince Philip: The Duke you don't know|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/8273569/Prince-Philip-the-Duke-you-dont-know.html|website=The Telegraph (UK)|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> The Queen and the children remained in the UK. On the return leg of the journey, Philip's private secretary, [[Michael Parker (courtier)|Mike Parker]], was sued for divorce by his wife. As with Townsend, the press still portrayed divorce as a scandal and eventually Parker resigned. He later said that the Duke was very supportive and \"the Queen was wonderful throughout. She regarded divorce as a sadness, not a hanging offence.\"<ref>Quoted in Brandreth, p. 287</ref> In a public show of support, the Queen created Parker a Commander of the [[Royal Victorian Order]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 287, 289</ref>\n\nFurther press reports claimed that the Queen and the Duke were drifting apart, which enraged the Duke and dismayed the Queen, who issued a strongly worded denial.<ref>Brandreth, p. 288</ref> On 22 February 1957, she granted her husband the style and title of a Prince of the United Kingdom by [[Letters Patent]], and it was gazetted that he was to be known as \"His Royal Highness The Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh\".<ref name=\"prince\">{{London Gazette |issue=41009 |date=22 February 1957 |page=1209}}</ref> Philip was appointed to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] on 14 October 1957, taking his [[Oath of Allegiance (Canada)|Oath of Allegiance]] before the Queen in person at her Canadian residence, [[Rideau Hall]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bousfield |first=Arthur |author2=Toffoli, Gary |title=Fifty Years the Queen |publisher=Dundurn Press |year=2002 |location=Toronto |page=12 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=w8l5reK7NjoC&printsec=frontcover&q= |isbn=1-55002-360-8}}</ref> Remarks he made two years later to the [[Canadian Medical Association]] on the subject of youth and sport were taken as a suggestion that Canadian children were out of shape. This was at first considered \"tactless\", but Philip was later admired for his encouragement of physical fitness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/prince-philip-hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh/ |title=Prince Philip (HRH The Duke of Edinburgh) |work=The Canadian Encyclopedia |publisher=Historica Canada |accessdate=23 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609155631/http://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/prince-philip-hrh-the-duke-of-edinburgh/ |archive-date=9 June 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Canada in 1969, Philip spoke about his views on republicanism:\n{{Quote|It is a complete misconception to imagine that the monarchy exists in the interests of the monarch. It doesn't. It exists in the interests of the people. If at any time any nation decides that the system is unacceptable, then it is up to them to change it.<ref>Brandreth, p. 50</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, at Salford University in 1967.jpg|thumb|Visiting Salford University in 1967]]\n\nPhilip is [[Patronage|patron]] of some 800 organisations, particularly focused on the environment, industry, sport, and education. His first solo engagement as Duke of Edinburgh was in March 1948, presenting prizes at the boxing finals of the London Federation of Boys' Clubs at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke of Edinburgh attended boxing match as first of 22,000 official duties |url=https://www.metro.news/philip-attended-boxing-match-as-first-of-22000-official-solo-engagements/695455/ |website=Metro News |access-date=23 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124041504/https://www.metro.news/philip-attended-boxing-match-as-first-of-22000-official-solo-engagements/695455/ |archive-date=24 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was president of the [[National Playing Fields Association]] (now known as [[Fields in Trust]]) for 64 years, from 1947 until his grandson Prince William took over the role in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince William succeeds the Duke of Edinburgh as he gives up royal role|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/390492/Prince-William-succeeds-the-Duke-of-Edinburgh-as-he-gives-up-royal-role|accessdate=7 December 2016|work=Daily Express|date=9 April 2013}}</ref> He served as UK president of the [[World Wildlife Fund]] from 1961 to 1982, international president from 1981, and president emeritus from 1996.<ref name=\"royanikkhah\" /> In 1952, he became patron of The Industrial Society (since renamed [[The Work Foundation]]).<ref name=\"basil\" /> He was president of the [[International Equestrian Federation]] from 1964 to 1986,<ref name=\"equestrianfederation\">{{cite web|title=Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, Talks Love of and Involvement in Combined Driving|url=https://www.usequestrian.org/media/press-releases/prince-philip-duke-of-edinburgh-talks-love-of-involvement-in-combined-driving-in-first-post-retirement-interview-at-royal-windsor-horse-show|website=US Equestrian|publisher=US Equestrian Communications Department|accessdate=12 December 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212152435/https://www.usequestrian.org/media/press-releases/prince-philip-duke-of-edinburgh-talks-love-of-involvement-in-combined-driving-in-first-post-retirement-interview-at-royal-windsor-horse-show|archivedate=12 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has served as chancellor of the universities of Cambridge, [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], [[University of Salford|Salford]], and [[University of Wales|Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Activitiesandinterests.aspx |title=The Duke of Edinburgh: Activities and interests |publisher=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106114941/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheDukeofEdinburgh/Activitiesandinterests.aspx |archivedate=6 November 2011 }}</ref> In 2017, the [[British Heart Foundation]] thanked Prince Philip for being its patron for 55 years, during which time, in addition to organising fundraisers, he \"supported the creation of nine BHF-funded centres of excellence\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Chief Executive thanks Prince Philip for his commitment as Patron|url=https://www.bhf.org.uk/news-from-the-bhf/news-archive/2017/may/our-chief-executive-thanks-prince-philip-for-his-work-as-patron|website=News Archive|publisher=British Heart Foundation|accessdate=30 December 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230024120/https://www.bhf.org.uk/news-from-the-bhf/news-archive/2017/may/our-chief-executive-thanks-prince-philip-for-his-work-as-patron|archivedate=30 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is an Honorary Fellow of [[St Edmund's College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/people/hrh-prince-philip-duke-edinburgh|title=St Edmund's College \u2013 University of Cambridge|website=www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910204442/http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/people/hrh-prince-philip-duke-edinburgh|archive-date=10 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Charles and Diana====\n[[File:Duke of Edinburgh 33 Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|upright|Philip in 1992]]\n\nAt the beginning of 1981, Philip wrote to his eldest son, Charles, counselling him to make up his mind to either propose to [[Lady Diana Spencer]] or break off their courtship.<ref>Brandreth, p. 344; Lacey, p. 276</ref> Charles felt pressured by his father to make a decision and did so, proposing to Diana in February.<ref>Brandreth, p. 346; Lacey, pp. 277\u2013278</ref> [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Lady Diana Spencer|They married]] five months later. By 1992, the marriage of the Prince and Princess of Wales had broken down. The Queen and Philip hosted a meeting between Charles and Diana, trying to effect a reconciliation, but without success.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 348\u2013349</ref> Philip wrote to Diana, expressing his disappointment at both Charles's and her extra-marital affairs, and asking her to examine both his and her behaviour from the other's point of view.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 349\u2013351</ref> She found the letters hard to take, but nevertheless appreciated that he was acting with good intent.<ref>Brandreth, pp. 351\u2013353</ref> Charles and Diana separated and later divorced.\n\nA year after the divorce, [[Death of Diana, Princess of Wales|Diana was killed in a car crash]] in Paris on 31 August 1997. At the time, the Duke was on holiday at Balmoral with the extended royal family. In their grief, Diana's two sons, Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry|Harry]], wanted to attend church and so their grandparents took them that morning.<ref name=brandreth1>Brandreth, p. 358</ref> For five days, the Queen and the Duke shielded their grandsons from the ensuing press interest by keeping them at Balmoral, where they could grieve in private.<ref name=\"brandreth1\" /> The royal family's seclusion caused public dismay,<ref name=\"brandreth1\" /> but the public mood changed after a live broadcast made by the Queen on 5&nbsp;September.<ref name=\"brandreth2\">Brandreth, p. 359</ref> Uncertain as to whether they should walk behind her coffin during the [[Funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales|funeral procession]], Diana's sons hesitated.<ref name=\"brandreth2\" /> Philip told William, \"If you don't walk, I think you'll regret it later. If I walk, will you walk with me?\"<ref name=\"brandreth2\" /> On the day of the funeral, Philip, William, Harry, Charles, and Diana's brother, [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Earl Spencer]], walked through London behind her bier.\n\nOver the next few years, [[Mohamed Fayed]], whose son [[Dodi Fayed]] was also killed in the crash, claimed that Prince Philip had ordered the death of Diana and that the accident was staged. The inquest into the Princess of Wales's death concluded in 2008 that there was no evidence of a conspiracy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7322204.stm |work=BBC News |title=Duke 'did not order Diana death' |date=31 March 2008 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====21st century====\nDuring [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|his wife's Golden Jubilee]] in 2002, the Duke was commended by the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the British House of Commons]] for his role in supporting the Queen during her reign. The Duke of Edinburgh's time as royal consort exceeds that of any other consort in British history;<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince Philip reaches milestone |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8005464.stm |accessdate=7 June 2013 |work=BBC News |date=18 April 2009}}</ref> however, [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] (his mother-in-law), who died aged 101, has had the longest lifespan to date. Philip is also the oldest ever male member of the British royal family, and the third longest-lived following [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]], and Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-04-19/philip-becomes-third-oldest-royal-in-british-history/|title=Prince Philip, 97, becomes third oldest royal (and oldest ever male) in British history - but who is number one?|publisher=ITV News|date=19 April 2019|accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, 2006.jpg|thumb|left|Philip in 2006]]\n\nIn April 2008, Philip was admitted to [[King Edward VII's Hospital]], London, for \"assessment and treatment\" for a chest infection, though he walked into the hospital unaided and recovered quickly,<ref>{{cite web| title=Duke of Edinburgh is in hospital|publisher=BBC News| date=4 April 2008| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7333280.stm| accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> and was discharged three days later to recuperate at [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Prince discharged from hospital|publisher=BBC News| date=6 April 2008| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7330697.stm| accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> In August, the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' reported that he was suffering from [[prostate cancer]]. Buckingham Palace, which usually refuses to comment on rumours of ill health, claimed that the report was an invasion of privacy and issued a statement denying the story.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement From Buckingham Palace Following the Evening Standard's Story Entitled 'Prince Philip Defies Cancer Scare' |publisher=Buckingham Palace |date=6 August 2008 |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2008/STATEMENTFROMBUCKINGHAMPALACEFOLLOWINGTHEEVENINGST.aspx |accessdate=20 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202213153/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2008/STATEMENTFROMBUCKINGHAMPALACEFOLLOWINGTHEEVENINGST.aspx |archivedate=2 December 2010 }}</ref> The newspaper retracted the report and admitted it was untrue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/08/08/british-paper-retracts-story-claiming-prince-philip-has-prostate-cancer/|title=British Paper Retracts Story Claiming Prince Philip Has Prostate Cancer|publisher=Fox News|date=8 August 2008|access-date=1 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110040853/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/08/08/british-paper-retracts-story-claiming-prince-philip-has-prostate-cancer/|archive-date=10 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.smh.com.au/world/paper-apologises-for-prince-philip-story-20080808-3sea.html|title=Paper apologises for Prince Philip story|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, in an interview marking his 90th birthday he said that he would now slow down and reduce his duties, stating that he had \"done [his] bit\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Prince Philip Turns 90 and Vows to 'Slow Down'|publisher=BBC News| date=10 June 2011| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13722857| accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref> His wife, the Queen, gave him the title [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]] for his 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13730067 |title=New title for Duke of Edinburgh as he turns 90 |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2011 |accessdate=10 June 2011}}</ref> While staying at [[Sandringham House]], the royal residence in Norfolk, on 23 December 2011, the Duke suffered chest pains and was taken to the cardio-thoracic unit at [[Papworth Hospital]], Cambridgeshire, where he underwent successful [[Percutaneous coronary intervention|coronary angioplasty]] and [[Coronary stent|stenting]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Peter Hunt |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16323794 |title=Prince Philip has heart procedure at Papworth Hospital |publisher=BBC News|date=24 December 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref> He was discharged on 27 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-16337357|title=Duke of Edinburgh leaves hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=27 December 2011|accessdate=27 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HM The Queen and Prince Philip.JPG|thumb|On the balcony of [[Buckingham Palace]], 2012]]\n\nOn 4 June 2012, during the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|celebrations]] in honour of his wife's [[Diamond Jubilee]], Philip was taken from Windsor Castle to King Edward VII's Hospital suffering from a bladder infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itn.co.uk/home/46928/Duke+of+Edinburgh+hospitalised|title=Duke of Edinburgh hospitalised|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012|publisher=[[ITN]]}}{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Philip in hospital and to miss Diamond Jubilee concert|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18325522|work=BBC News|accessdate=4 June 2012|date=4 June 2012}}</ref> He was released from hospital on 9 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/09/world/europe/uk-prince-philip/index.html?hpt=hp_t2|title=Britain's Prince Philip released from hospital in time for his birthday|publisher=CNN|date=9 June 2012}}</ref> After a recurrence of infection in August 2012, while staying at [[Balmoral Castle]], he was admitted to [[Aberdeen Royal Infirmary]] for five nights as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19317991|title=Prince Philip leaves Aberdeen hospital after five nights|work=BBC News|date=20 August 2012}}</ref> In June 2013, Philip was admitted to the [[London Clinic]] for an [[Exploratory surgery|exploratory operation]] on his abdomen, spending 11 days in hospital.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Philip leaves hospital, will recuperate at Windsor Castle|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/17/world/europe/uk-prince-philip-hospital/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=17 June 2013|date=17 June 2013}}</ref> On 21 May 2014, the Prince appeared in public with a bandage on his right hand after a \"minor procedure\" was performed in Buckingham Palace the preceding day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Duke of Edinburgh has 'minor procedure' on hand|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-27507555|accessdate=7 August 2014|work=BBC News|date=21 May 2014}}</ref> In June 2017, he was taken from Windsor to London and admitted to King Edward VII's Hospital after being diagnosed with an infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/21/duke-edinburgh-admitted-hospital-infection/|title=Prince Philip admitted to hospital with infection and misses State Opening of Parliament|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Hannah|last=Furness|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref> He spent two nights in the hospital and was unable to attend the State Opening of Parliament and Royal Ascot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/21/prince-philip-admitted-to-hospital-with-infection|title=Prince Philip to spend second night in hospital|work=The Guardian|first=Caroline|last=Davies|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/22/europe/prince-philip-discharged-hospital/index.html|title=UK's Prince Philip Discharged from Hospital after Treatment for Infection|publisher=CNN|first=Eliza|last=Mackintosh|date=22 June 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nPrince Philip retired from his royal duties on 2 August 2017, meeting Royal Marines in his final solo public engagement, aged 96. Since 1952 he had completed 22,219 solo engagements. Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] thanked him for \"a remarkable lifetime of service\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/prince-philip-prepares-for-final-royal-engagement-10970314|title=Prince Philip carries out final royal engagement before retirement|date=2 August 2017|publisher=Sky News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40798469|title=Prince Philip carries out final official engagement|work=BBC News|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> On 20 November 2017, he celebrated his 70th wedding anniversary with the Queen, which made her the first British monarch to celebrate a platinum wedding anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/nov/20/queen-prince-philip-portraits-platinum-wedding-70th-anniversary|title=Queen and Prince Philip portraits released to mark 70th anniversary|date=20 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2018, Philip was admitted to King Edward VII's Hospital for a planned [[hip replacement]], which took place the next day. This came after the Duke missed the annual Maundy and Easter Sunday services. On 12 April his daughter, Princess Anne, spent about 50 minutes in the hospital and afterwards said her father was \"on good form\". He was discharged the following day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43755269|title=Duke of Edinburgh leaves hospital|date=13 April 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=13 April 2018}}</ref> On 19 May, six weeks later, he attended the [[Wedding of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle|wedding]] of his grandson Prince Harry to [[Meghan Markle]] and was able to walk with the Queen unaided.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cpwpy79d6dxt/royal-wedding-2018|title=Royal Wedding 2018|website=BBC News|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref> That October, he accompanied the Queen to the [[Wedding of Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank|wedding]] of their granddaughter [[Princess Eugenie]] to [[Jack Brooksbank]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/in-pictures-45829410|title=Princess Eugenie wedding in pictures: Splendid hats and gusts of wind|work=BBC News|date=12 October 2018}}</ref> with ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reporting that Philip works on a \"wake up and see how I feel\" basis when deciding whether to attend an event or not.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2018/10/09/duke-edinburgh-will-decide-day-attends-royal-wedding/|title=Duke of Edinburgh 'will decide at last moment' whether he attends royal wedding of Princess Eugenie|work=The Telegraph|first=Camilla|last=Tominey|date=9 October 2018|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2019, 97-year-old Philip was involved in a car crash as he pulled out onto a main road near the [[Sandringham Estate]]. An official statement said he was uninjured. An eyewitness who came to the prince's aid described having to wipe blood off his hands.<ref name=\"furness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/01/18/road-prince-philip-crashed-expected-have-speed-limit-reduced/|title=Prince Philip crash: Duke 'asked if everyone else was alright' after car 'tumbled' across road leaving him bleeding|date=18 January 2019|accessdate=18 January 2019|author=Hannah Furness|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> The driver and a passenger of the other car were injured and taken to hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jan/20/prince-philip-has-not-said-sorry-for-car-crash-injured-woman-claims|title=Prince Philip has not said sorry for car crash, injured woman claims|author=Haroon Siddique|date=20 January 2019|accessdate=20 January 2019|website=The Guardian}}</ref> Philip attended hospital the next morning as a precaution.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jan/18/prince-philip-car-crash-norfolk-police-to-investigate|title=Prince Philip undergoes hospital checks after car crash|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2019|author=Caroline Davies|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He apologised,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/01/27/prince-philip-apologises-mother-involved-car-crash/|title=Prince Philip sends personal apology to victims of Sandringham car crash|website=The Telegraph|date=27 January 2019|accessdate=9 February 2019|author=Victoria Ward}}</ref> and three weeks later voluntarily surrendered his driving licence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/feb/09/prince-philip-surrenders-his-driving-licence|title=Prince Philip gives up driving licence three weeks after car crash|date=9 February 2019|accessdate=9 February 2019|website=The Guardian|author=Lin Jenkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47186875|title=Prince Philip, 97, gives up driving licence|publisher=BBC|date=9 February 2019|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> On 14 February the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced that prosecuting Philip would not be in the public interest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/feb/14/prince-philip-will-not-be-prosecuted-over-car-crash-cps|title=Prince Philip will not be prosecuted over car crash, says CPS|date=14 February 2019|accessdate=14 February 2019|website=The Guardian|author=Owen Bowcott}}</ref> The Duke is still allowed to drive around private estates, and was seen behind the wheel in the grounds of Windsor Castle in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/prince-philip-spotted-behind-wheel-for-first-time-since-giving-up-licence-918660.html|title=Prince Philip 'spotted behind wheel for first time since giving up licence'|newspaper=Irish Examiner|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=19 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418181509/https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/prince-philip-spotted-behind-wheel-for-first-time-since-giving-up-licence-918660.html|archive-date=18 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 20\u201324 December 2019, Philip stayed at King Edward VII's Hospital, in a visit described by Buckingham Palace as a \"precautionary measure\". He had not been seen in public since attending [[Lady Gabriella Kingston]]'s wedding in May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50870869|title=Prince Philip taken to hospital as a 'precautionary measure'|work=BBC News|date=20 December 2019|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personality and image==\n[[File:Prins Philip (1982).jpg|thumb|Philip at the World Championship Coach-and-fours, 1982]]\nPhilip played [[polo]] until 1971, when he started to compete in [[Combined driving|carriage driving]], a sport which he helped to expand; the early rule book was drafted under his supervision.<ref>Heald, pp. 212\u2013214</ref> He was also a keen yachtsman and struck up a friendship in 1949 with [[Uffa Fox]], in [[Cowes]]. Philip and the Queen regularly attended [[Cowes Week]] in [[HMY Britannia|HMY ''Britannia'']]. His first airborne flying lesson took place in 1952; by his 70th birthday he had accrued 5,150 pilot hours.<ref>Heald, pp. 148\u2013149</ref> He was presented with [[Royal Air Force]] wings in 1953.<ref>{{cite web|last=Monarchy |first=British |url=https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/ArmedForces/TheRoyalAirForce.aspx |title=The Royal Air Force |website=Official website of the British Monarchy |accessdate=6 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617152205/http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/ArmedForces/TheRoyalAirForce.aspx |archivedate=17 June 2013 }}</ref> In April 2014, it was reported that an old [[British Pathe]] newsreel film had been discovered of Philip's 1962 two-month flying tour of [[South America]]. Filmed sitting alongside Philip at the aircraft's controls was his co-pilot [[Family of Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Captain Peter Middleton]], the grandfather of the Duke's granddaughter-in-law, [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sparkes|first=Matthew|title=Royal couples' grandparents' jet-age meeting|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/10779536/Pictured-Royal-couples-grandparents-jet-age-meeting.html|work=Daily Telegraph|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tominey|first1=Camilla|title=Truth behind Prince George's love of aviation|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/643885/Truth-behind-Prince-George-love-aviation|location=UK |work=Daily Express |date=14 February 2016|accessdate=19 February 2015|quote=It (the photograph) shows the Duchess of Cambridge's grandfather, Captain Peter Middleton, with Prince Philip in 1962...}}</ref>\n[[File:Her Majesty the Queen at Breakfast.jpg|thumb|''Her Majesty the Queen at Breakfast'' painted by her husband in 1957. Biographer [[Robert Lacey]] described the painting as \"a tender portrayal, impressionistic in style, with brushstrokes that are charmingly soft and fuzzy\".<ref>Lacey, p. 368</ref>]]\n\nHe has painted with oils, and collected artworks, including contemporary [[cartoon]]s, which hang at Buckingham Palace, Windsor Castle, Sandringham House, and Balmoral Castle. [[Hugh Casson]] described Philip's own artwork as \"exactly what you'd expect&nbsp;... totally direct, no hanging about. Strong colours, vigorous brushstrokes.\"<ref>Heald, p. 253</ref>\n\nPhilip's down-to-earth manner was attested to by a White House butler who recalled that, on a visit in 1979, Philip had engaged him and a fellow butler in a conversation and poured them drinks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/18/obama-inauguration|location=London |newspaper=The Guardian| first=Christopher|last=Goodwin|title=I'm tickled to death. I never thought I'd see such a thing|date=18 January 2009}}</ref> As well as a reputation for bluntness and plain speaking,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-13682432|title=Prince Philip at 90 on a lifetime of speaking his mind|work=BBC News|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> Philip is noted for occasionally making observations and jokes that have been construed as either funny, or as gaffes: awkward, [[politically incorrect]], or even offensive, but sometimes perceived as stereotypical of someone of his age and background.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/5360412.stm |title=Caught on tape: Infamous gaffes|work=BBC News|date= 19 September 2006|accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,23745347-5007146,00.html |title=Prince Philip right to have a dig at Durie |website=News.com.au |author=Blair, Tim|date=23 May 2008 |accessdate=12 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108233956/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C23599%2C23745347-5007146%2C00.html |archivedate=8 January 2009 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/am/content/2006/s1660067.htm |title=AM&nbsp;\u2013 Prince Philip reminded of blunders on his 85th birthday |work=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20000423/ai_n13948104 |title=The Secret Life of Prince Philip |newspaper=Sunday Herald |date=23 April 2000 |accessdate=12 October 2008 |first=Stephen |last=Naysmith |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206001454/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20000423/ai_n13948104 |archivedate=6 December 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/05/AR2007050500981_pf.html|title=Prince Philip Has a Mouthful Of a Title. And, Often, His Foot|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=12 October 2008|first=Paul|last=Duggan}}</ref> In an address to the General Dental Council in 1960, he jokingly coined a new word for his blunders: \"Dontopedalogy is the science of opening your mouth and putting your foot in it, a science which I have practised for a good many years.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Dolby, Karen |title=The Wicked Wit of Queen Elizabeth II|publisher= Michael O'Mara Books|location= London |date=2015|page= 44}}</ref> Later in life he suggested his comments may have contributed to the perception that he is \"a cantankerous old sod\".<ref>Prince Philip quoted in Brandreth, p. 7</ref>\n\nThe historian [[David Starkey]] described him as a kind of \"HRH [[Victor Meldrew]]\".<ref>Starkey, speaking on BBC News Radio Four, 10 June 2011</ref> For example, in May 1999, British newspapers accused Philip of insulting deaf children at a pop concert in Wales by saying, \"No wonder you are deaf listening to this row.\"<ref>Brandreth, p. 46</ref> Later Philip wrote, \"The story is largely invention. It so happens that my mother was quite seriously deaf and I have been Patron of the Royal National Institute for the Deaf for ages, so it's hardly likely that I would do any such thing.\"<ref>Letter of 4 June 1999 quoted in Brandreth, p. 46</ref> When he and the Queen met Stephen Menary, an army cadet blinded by an IRA bomb, and the Queen enquired how much sight he retained, Philip quipped: \"Not a lot, judging by the tie he's wearing.\" Menary later said: \"I think he just tries to put people at ease by trying to make a joke. I certainly didn't take any offence.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/6805975/Duke-of-Edinburgh-gaffes-by-mocking-blind-boy.html|title=Duke of Edinburgh gaffes by mocking blind boy|last=Leach|first=By Ben|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref>\n\nDuring a state visit to China in 1986, in a private conversation with British students from [[Xi'an]]'s [[Northwest University (China)|North West University]], Philip joked, \"If you stay here much longer, you'll go slit-eyed<!--Prince Philip insists he said \"slit-eyed\" and not \"slitty-eyed\": see Heald, p. 245-->.\"<ref>Heald, pp. 244\u2013245; Lacey, p. 303</ref> The British press reported on the remark as indicative of racial intolerance, but the Chinese authorities were reportedly unconcerned. Chinese students studying in the UK, an official explained, were often told in jest not to stay away too long, lest they go \"round-eyed\".<ref>Lacey, p. 304; see also Heald, p. 245 for a Hong Kong version of the \"round-eyed\" joke.</ref> His comment had no effect on [[China\u2013United Kingdom relations|Sino-British relations]], but it shaped his own reputation.<ref>Heald, p. 246; Lacey, p. 304</ref>\n\n==Portrayals==\nPhilip has been portrayed by several actors including [[Stewart Granger]] (''[[The Royal Romance of Charles and Diana]]'', 1982), [[Christopher Lee]] (''Charles & Diana: A Royal Love Story'', 1982), [[David Threlfall]] (''[[The Queen's Sister]]'', 2005), [[James Cromwell]] (''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'', 2006), and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]], Finn Elliot and [[Tobias Menzies]] (''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'', 2016 onwards).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43581479|title=The Crown: Tobias Menzies cast as new Prince Philip|work=BBC|date=29 March 2018|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrince Philip appears as a fictional character in [[Nevil Shute]]'s novel ''[[In the Wet]]'' (1952), [[Paul Gallico]]'s novel ''Mrs. 'Arris Goes to Moscow'' (1974), [[Tom Clancy]]'s novel ''[[Patriot Games]]'' (1987), and [[Sue Townsend]]'s novel ''[[The Queen and I (novel)|The Queen and I]]'' (1992).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/25/books/the-british-novelist-who-turned-a-class-system-upside-down.html|title=The British Novelist Who Turned A Class System Upside Down|last=Cassidy|first=Suzanne|date=25 December 1993|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-09-16}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nThe prince has authored a number of books:\n* ''Selected Speeches&nbsp;\u2013 1948\u201355'' (1957, revised paperback edition published by [[Nabu Press]] in 2011) {{ISBN|978-1245671330}}\n* ''Selected Speeches&nbsp;\u2013 1956\u201359'' (1960)\n* ''Birds from Britannia'' (1962) (published in the United States as ''Seabirds from Southern Waters'') {{ISBN|978-1163699294}}\n* ''Wildlife Crisis'' with [[James Fisher (naturalist)|James Fisher]] (1970) {{ISBN|978-0402125112}}\n* ''The Environmental Revolution: Speeches on Conservation, 1962\u20131977'' (1978) {{ISBN|978-0846414537}}\n* ''Competition Carriage Driving'' (1982) (published in France 1984, second edition 1984, revised edition 1994) {{ISBN|978-0851315942}}\n* ''A Question of Balance'' (1982) {{ISBN|978-0859550871}}\n* ''Men, Machines and Sacred Cows'' (1984) {{ISBN|978-0241111741}}\n* ''A Windsor Correspondence'' with [[Michael Ashley Mann|Michael Mann]] (1984) {{ISBN|978-0859551083}}\n* ''Down to Earth: Collected Writings and Speeches on Man and the Natural World 1961\u201387'' (1988) (paperback edition 1989, Japanese edition 1992) {{ISBN|978-0828907118}}\n* ''Survival or Extinction: A Christian Attitude to the Environment'' with Michael Mann (1989) {{ISBN|978-0859551588}}\n* ''Driving and Judging Dressage'' (1996) {{ISBN|978-0851316666}}\n* ''30 Years On, and Off, the Box Seat'' (2004) {{ISBN|978-0851318981}}\n\nForewords to:\n*''Royal Australian Navy 1911\u20131961 Jubilee Souvenir'' issued by authority of the Department of the Navy, Canberra (1961)\n* ''The Concise British Flora in Colour'' by [[William Keble Martin]], [[Random House|Ebury Press]]/ [[Michael Joseph (publisher)|Michael Joseph]] (1965)\n* ''Kurt Hahn'' by Hermann R\u00f6hrs and Hilary Tunstall-Behrens (1970)\n* ''The Art of Driving'' by Max Pape (1982) {{ISBN|978-0851313399}}\n*''Yachting and the Royal Prince Alfred Yacht Club'' by Graeme Norman (1988) {{ISBN|978-0867770674}}\n*''[[National Maritime Museum]] Guide to Maritime Britain'' by Keith Wheatley, (2000)\n* ''The Royal Yacht Britannia: The Official History'' by Richard Johnstone-Bryden, [[Conway Publishing|Conway Maritime Press]] (2003) {{ISBN|978-0851779379}}\n* ''1953: The Crowning Year of Sport'' by Jonathan Rice, (2003)\n* ''British Flags and Emblems'' by [[Graham Bartram]], Tuckwell Press (2004) {{ISBN|978-1862322974}}\n* ''Chariots of War'' by Robert Hobson, Ulric Publication (2004) {{ISBN|978-0954199715}}\n* ''RMS Queen Mary 2 Manual: An Insight into the Design, Construction and Operation of the World's Largest Ocean Liner'' by [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]], Haynes Publishing (2014)\n* ''The Triumph of a Great Tradition: The Story of Cunard's 175 Years'' by Eric Flounders and Michael Gallagher, Lily Publications (2014){{ISBN?}}\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n{{Main|List of titles and honours of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n[[File:Prince Philip as Colonel-in-Chief of the Royal Canadian Regiment.jpg|thumb|The Duke of Edinburgh, [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Royal Canadian Regiment]], presenting the 3rd Battalion with their Regimental Colours in April 2013]]\nPhilip has held a number of titles throughout his life. Originally holding the title and style of a [[prince of Greece and Denmark]], Philip abandoned these royal titles prior to his marriage, and was thereafter created a British [[duke]], among other noble titles. The Queen formally issued letters patent in 1957 making Philip a [[British prince]].<ref name=prince />\n\nWhen addressing the Duke of Edinburgh, as with any male member of the royal family except the monarch, the rules of etiquette are to address him the first time as ''Your Royal Highness'', and thereafter as ''Sir''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/etiquette/british-behaviour/r-to-s/royalty.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112125544/http://www.debretts.com/etiquette/british-behaviour/r-to-s/royalty.aspx|archivedate=2010-11-12|title=Royalty \u2013 Debrett's Guide to British Behaviour|date=12 November 2010|publisher=|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Honours and honorary military appointments===\nThe Duke of Edinburgh was appointed by King George VI to the [[Order of the Garter]] on 19 November 1947, the eve of his wedding. Since then, Philip has received 17 different appointments and decorations in the Commonwealth, and 48 from foreign states. The inhabitants of some villages on the island of [[Tanna (island)|Tanna, Vanuatu]] [[Prince Philip Movement|worship Prince Philip as a god]]; the islanders possess portraits of the Duke and hold feasts on his birthday.<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=Nick|title=Is Prince Philip an island god?|publisher=BBC News|date=10 June 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/6734469.stm|accessdate=12 October 2008|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Yaohnanen Tribesmen Show Pictures of 2007 Visit with Prince Philip.jpg|thumb|[[Ni-Vanuatu]] with pictures of Philip]]\nUpon his wife's accession to the throne in 1952, the Duke was appointed Admiral of the [[Sea Cadet Corps (United Kingdom)|Sea Cadet Corps]], [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the British [[Army Cadet Force]], and [[Air Commodore-in-Chief]] of the [[Air Training Corps]].<ref>Heald, p. 111</ref> The following year, he was appointed to the equivalent positions in Canada and made [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]], [[Captain General Royal Marines]], [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]], and [[Marshal of the Royal Air Force]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>Heald, pp. 264\u2013267</ref> Subsequent military appointments were made in [[New Zealand]] and [[Australia]].<ref>Brandreth, pp. 407\u2013408; Heald, pp. 264\u2013267</ref> In 1975, he was appointed [[Colonel]] of the [[Grenadier Guards]], a position he handed over to his son Andrew in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/duke-york-appointed-colonel-grenadier-guards|title=The Duke of York is appointed Colonel of the Grenadier Guards|publisher=Royal Household|date=1 December 2017}}</ref> On 16 December 2015, his role as Honorary Air Commodore-in-Chief was handed over to the Duchess of Cambridge.\n\nTo celebrate his 90th birthday, the Queen appointed him [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/duke-edinburgh-appointed-lord-high-admiral|title=The Duke of Edinburgh appointed Lord High Admiral|publisher=royal.uk|date=10 June 2011|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> as well as to the highest ranks available in all three branches of the [[Canadian Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=605239|last=Office of the Prime Minister of Canada|title=PM announces the appointment of His Royal Highness the Duke of Edinburgh to the highest ranks of the Canadian Armed Forces|date=10 June 2011|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=10 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116103058/http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=605239|archive-date=16 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn their 70th wedding anniversary, 20 November 2017, the Queen appointed him Knight Grand Cross (GCVO) of the [[Royal Victorian Order]], making him the first British national since his uncle Earl Mountbatten of Burma to be entitled to wear the breast stars of four orders of chivalry in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Furness|first1=Hannah|title=Queen grants new honour to Prince Philip for 70th wedding anniversary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/20/queen-grants-new-honour-prince-philip-70th-wedding-anniversary/|accessdate=22 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = Coat of Arms of Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.svg\n|bannerimage = Royal Standard of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.svg\n|badgeimage =\n|notes = Following his marriage to Princess Elizabeth until 1949, Prince Philip's arms featured a differenced version of the [[royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom]], derived from his ancestor [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Princess Alice]].<ref name=boutell/><br />Unlike the arms used by other members of the royal family, the Duke's arms no longer features the royal arms of the United Kingdom, as he was granted new arms by King George VI in 1949. However, they do feature elements representing Greece and Denmark, from which he is descended in the male line; the [[Battenberg family|Mountbatten family]] arms, from which he is descended in the female line; and the City of [[Edinburgh]].\n|year_adopted = 19 November 1947\n|escutcheon = '''From 1949:'''<br />[[Quartering (heraldry)|Quarterly]]: First Or, sem\u00e9e of hearts Gules, three lions passant in pale Azure (For [[coat of arms of Denmark|Denmark]]), Second Azure, a cross Argent (For [[national emblem of Greece|Greece]]), Third Argent, two pallets Sable (For Battenberg or Mountbatten), Fourth Argent, upon a rock Proper a castle triple towered Sable, masoned Argent, windows, port, turret-caps and vanes Gules (For [[Coat of arms of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]]), the whole surrounded by the Garter.<ref name=pinches>Pinches, J. H. & R. V., The Royal Heraldry of England, 1974, Heraldry Today.</ref>\n|helm =Upon a coronet of a son of the sovereign Proper, the royal helm Or<ref name=pinches/>\n|crest =Issuant from a ducal coronet Or, a plume of five ostrich feathers alternately Sable and Argent;\n|torse =Mantling Or and ermine\n|supporters = Dexter, a representation of a [[wild man#Heraldry|wild man]] girt about the loins with a lion skin, crowned with a chaplet of oak leaves, holding in the dexter hand a club Proper (from the Danish and Greek royal coat of arms); sinister, a lion queue fourch\u00e9e ducally crowned Or and gorged with a naval coronet Azure;\n|compartment =\n|motto = '''GOD IS MY HELP'''\n|orders = The [[Order of the Garter]] ribbon<br />'''HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE'''<br />''(Shamed be he who thinks evil of it)''\n|other_elements =\n|banner = A banner of the Duke's arms is used as his personal standard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofedinburgh.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113231609/http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofedinburgh.html|archivedate=2009-01-13|title=Duke of Edinburgh|date=13 January 2009|publisher=|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n|badge =\n|symbolism = The arms of Denmark and Greece, represent the Duke of Edinburgh's familial lineage. The arms of the City of Edinburgh represent Philip's dukedom. The naval crown collar alludes to the Duke's naval career.\n|previous_versions = [[File:Arms of Philip Mountbatten (1947-1949).svg|right|100px]]\n'''From 1947 to 1949''':<br />\n\"[[Coat of arms of the Kingdom of Greece|Arms of Greece]] surmounted by an inescutcheon of the arms of Denmark; and over all in the first quarter the arms of [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Princess Alice]], daughter of [[Queen Victoria]], viz, the [[Royal Arms of the United Kingdom|Royal Arms]] differenced with a label of three points argent, the middle point charged with a rose gules and each of the others with an ermine spot. The shield is encircled by the Garter and ensigned with a princely coronet of crosses patt\u00e9e and fleurs-de-lis, above which is placed a barred helm affronte, and thereon the crest; out of a ducal coronet or, a plume of five ostrich feathers alternately sable and argent. The supporters are, dexter, the figure of Hercules proper, and sinister, a lion queue fourche ducally crowned or, gorged with a naval coronet azure.\"<ref name=boutell>Boutell's Heraldry. (1973) {{ISBN|0-7232-1708-4}}.</ref>\n}}\n\n==Issue==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Name\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Birth\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Marriage\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Their children\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Their grandchildren\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Spouse\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 14 November 1948\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 29 July 1981<br /><small>Divorced 28 August 1996</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Lady Diana Spencer]]\n| [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]]\n| [[Prince George of Cambridge]]<br />[[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge]]<br />[[Prince Louis of Cambridge]]\n|-\n| [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]]\n| [[Archie Mountbatten-Windsor]]\n|-\n| 9 April 2005\n| [[Camilla Parker Bowles]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 15 August 1950\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 14 November 1973<br /><small>Divorced 28 April 1992</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Mark Phillips]]\n| [[Peter Phillips]]\n| Savannah Phillips<br />Isla Phillips\n|-\n| [[Zara Tindall]]\n| Mia Tindall<br />Lena Tindall\n|-\n| 12 December 1992\n| [[Timothy Laurence]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" | [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 19 February 1960\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 23 July 1986<br /><small>Divorced 30 May 1996</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Sarah Ferguson]]\n| [[Princess Beatrice of York]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n| [[Princess Eugenie, Mrs Jack Brooksbank]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" | [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 10 March 1964\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 19 June 1999\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Sophie Rhys-Jones]]\n| [[Lady Louise Windsor]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n| [[James, Viscount Severn]]\n| {{N/A|None}}\n|}\n\n==Ancestry==\nBoth Philip and Queen Elizabeth II are great-great-grandchildren of [[Queen Victoria]], Elizabeth by descent from Victoria's eldest son, [[King Edward VII]], and Philip by descent from Victoria's second daughter, [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom|Princess Alice]]. Both are also descended from [[King Christian IX of Denmark]].\n\nPhilip is also related to the [[House of Romanov]] through both of his parents. He is a direct descendant of Emperor [[Nicholas I of Russia]] via his paternal grandmother Grand Duchess [[Olga Constantinovna of Russia]].<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Hugh Massingberd|last=Montgomery-Massingberd|first=Hugh (ed.)|year=1977|title=Burke's Royal Families of the World'', 1st edition''|location=London|publisher=Burke's Peerage|isbn=0-85011-023-8|ref=harv|pages=469\u2013474}}</ref> and his maternal grandmother, [[Princess Victoria of Hesse and by Rhine]], was a sister of [[Alexandra Feodorovna (Alix of Hesse)]], wife of [[Nicholas II of Russia|Emperor Nicholas II]].\n\nIn 1993, scientists were able to confirm the identity of the remains of several members of the Romanov family, more than 70 years after their [[execution of the Romanov family|massacre in 1918]], by comparing their [[mitochondrial DNA]] to living [[matrilineal]] relatives, including Philip. Philip, Alexandra, and her children are all descended from [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom]], the daughter of [[Queen Victoria]], through a purely female line.<ref name=gill>{{cite journal |last1=Gill |first1=Peter |last2=Ivanov |first2=Pavel L. |last3=Kimpton |first3=Colin |last4=Piercy |first4=Romelle |last5=Benson |first5=Nicola |last6=Tully |first6=Gillian |last7=Evett |first7=Ian |last8=Hagelberg |first8=Erika|authorlink8=Erika Hagelberg |last9=Sullivan |first9=Kevin |date=February 1994 |title=Identification of the remains of the Romanov family by DNA analysis |journal=Nature Genetics |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=130\u2013135 |doi=10.1038/ng0294-130 |pmid=8162066 }}</ref>\n\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes|align=center\n|ref=<ref>{{cite book |last=Louda |first=Ji\u0159\u00ed |last2=Maclagan |first2=Michael |authorlink2=Michael Maclagan |year=1999 |origyear=1981 |title=Lines of Succession: Heraldry of the Royal Families of Europe |edition=2nd |location=London |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=978-0-316-84820-6 |page=34 }}</ref><!--source for all 15-->\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]]\n|4= 4. [[George I of Greece]]\n|5= 5. [[Grand Duchess Olga Constantinovna of Russia]]\n|6= 6. [[Prince Louis of Battenberg]]\n|7= 7. [[Princess Victoria of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|8= 8. [[Christian IX of Denmark]]\n|9= 9. [[Louise of Hesse-Kassel|Princess Louise of Hesse-Kassel]]\n|10= 10. [[Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolayevich of Russia]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Alexandra of Saxe-Altenburg]]\n|12= 12. [[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|13= 13. [[Julia, Princess of Battenberg|Countess Julia von Hauke]]\n|14= 14. [[Louis IV, Grand Duke of Hesse|Louis IV, Grand Duke of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|15= 15. [[Princess Alice of the United Kingdom]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=fn}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Alexandra of Yugoslavia]] (1959). ''Prince Philip: A Family Portrait''. London: Hodder and Stoughton.\n* [[Basil Boothroyd|Boothroyd, Basil]] (1971). ''Prince Philip: An Informal Biography''. New York: McCall. {{ISBN|0-841-50116-5}}\n* [[Gyles Brandreth|Brandreth, Gyles]] (2004). ''Philip and Elizabeth: Portrait of a Marriage''. London: Century. {{ISBN|0-7126-6103-4}}\n* Eade, Philip (2011). ''Prince Philip: The Turbulent Early Life of the Man Who Married Queen Elizabeth II''. New York: St. Martin's Griffin. {{ISBN|978-1-250-01363-7}}\n* [[Tim Heald|Heald, Tim]] (1991). ''The Duke: A Portrait of Prince Philip''. London: Hodder and Stoughton. {{ISBN|0-340-54607-7}}\n* [[Robert Lacey|Lacey, Robert]] (2002). ''Royal: Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II''. London: Little, Brown. {{ISBN|0-316-85940-0}}\n* [[Hugo Vickers|Vickers, Hugo]] (2000). ''Alice, Princess Andrew of Greece''. London: Hamish Hamilton. {{ISBN|0-241-13686-5}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q80976|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no|c=category:Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n* [https://www.royal.uk/the-duke-of-edinburgh The Duke of Edinburgh at the Royal Family website]\n* {{Britannica|456258|Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/timelines/zqqy2nb Duke of Edinburgh's profile] on [[BBC]]\n* [http://www.dofe.org/ The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]\n* {{IMDb name|0697611|Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111206103156/http://www.life.com/gallery/58221/in-the-words-of-prince-philip#index/0 In the Words of Prince Philip]&nbsp;\u2013 slideshow by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]''\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/013568}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg]]|10 June|1921}}\n{{S-roy|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon]]|as=[[queen consort]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of British consorts|Consort of the British monarch]]\n|years=6 February 1952&nbs